const ANS_QUESTIONS = [{"cat":"network-design","q":"A financial services company needs to design a multi-region VPC architecture. What CIDR strategy enables non-conflicting connectivity?","options":["A. Use the same CIDR block in both regions","B. Use non-overlapping CIDR blocks and enable Transit Gateway peering","C. Use overlapping CIDR blocks with NAT instances","D. Use secondary CIDR blocks on all VPCs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit Gateway peering with non-overlapping CIDR blocks avoids routing conflicts while enabling consistent architecture scaling."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An enterprise needs hub-and-spoke topology across 12 AWS accounts. Which service provides centralized routing?","options":["A. VPC Peering with a central hub account","B. AWS Transit Gateway","C. AWS AppMesh for networking","D. VPN CloudHub"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit Gateway is the preferred solution for hub-and-spoke topologies, enabling simple attachment management and centralized routing."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company requires IPv6 support. What must be configured for full functionality?","options":["A. Assign IPv6 CIDR block to VPC only","B. Assign IPv6 CIDR block to VPC, subnets, and configure route table entries","C. Only assign IPv6 addresses to instances","D. Use NAT64 translation only"],"answer":1,"explain":"IPv6 requires explicit CIDR block assignment to VPC and subnets, plus route table entries pointing to egress-only IGW."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A healthcare provider needs redundant hybrid connectivity with consistent performance. What should be primary design?","options":["A. Single Direct Connect connection with VPN failover","B. Single VPN connection with Direct Connect as backup","C. Multiple Direct Connect Virtual Interfaces across diverse locations","D. Multiple VPNs on different endpoints"],"answer":2,"explain":"Multiple Direct Connect VIFs provide diverse physical connections with consistent performance and automatic failover."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An organization must implement PrivateLink for internal service sharing. What endpoint type enables this?","options":["A. Gateway endpoint","B. Interface endpoint with Network Load Balancer","C. Service endpoint with ALB","D. VPC peering with security groups"],"answer":1,"explain":"Interface endpoints with NLB enable secure PrivateLink service sharing across consumer VPCs."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company needs network segmentation with DMZ architecture. Which combination best implements this?","options":["A. Public and private subnets with NAT Gateway","B. Public, private, and protected subnets with multiple route tables","C. Only public subnets with security groups","D. Only private subnets with VPN endpoint"],"answer":1,"explain":"DMZ requires public (web), private (app), and protected (db) subnets with distinct route tables and rules."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A multi-tenant SaaS platform requires customer VPC isolation. What prevents IP conflicts while enabling communication?","options":["A. Shared VPC with separate subnets","B. Multiple VPCs with Transit Gateway and custom routing","C. VPC peering between all customer VPCs","D. Single VPC with overlapping CIDR blocks and NAT"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit Gateway with custom route policies enables isolated multi-tenant VPCs with non-overlapping CIDR blocks."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company needs routing between on-premises, multiple AWS regions, and AWS accounts. What service enables this?","options":["A. Route 53 health checks","B. AWS Global Accelerator","C. AWS Cloud WAN","D. AWS Wavelength"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Cloud WAN provides centralized management of global networking connecting on-premises, multiple regions, and accounts."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An organization requires DNS resolution from on-premises to AWS resources. What is recommended?","options":["A. Route 53 public hosted zone with on-premises forwarding","B. Route 53 Resolver endpoints with conditional forwarding","C. Simple Route 53 private hosted zone","D. On-premises DNS as primary authority"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 Resolver inbound/outbound endpoints enable hybrid DNS resolution in both directions."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A financial institution requires multiple transit routes and path selection. What Transit Gateway feature enables this?","options":["A. Transit Gateway route tables","B. Transit Gateway peering","C. Transit Gateway multicast","D. Transit Gateway NAT"],"answer":0,"explain":"Transit Gateway route tables support multiple routes per attachment and enable flexible path selection."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company must quickly design network for 50 instances across 2 AZs. What minimum subnet count ensures flexibility?","options":["A. One subnet per AZ","B. One public and one private per AZ","C. One public, private, protected per AZ","D. Flexible based only on current needs"],"answer":2,"explain":"Three-tier architecture in each AZ provides web, app, and database isolation from the start."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A healthcare organization must meet HIPAA compliance. What architecture satisfies requirements?","options":["A. Public subnet with encryption only","B. Isolated subnets with private connectivity and strict egress controls","C. Subnets with NAT Gateway for anonymization","D. VPC peering with external providers"],"answer":1,"explain":"HIPAA requires network isolation, preventing direct internet access to PHI with restricted egress."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A startup requires low-latency on-premises to AWS connectivity with limited budget. What is most cost-effective?","options":["A. Direct Connect with dedicated connection","B. Site-to-Site VPN over internet","C. Multiple redundant connections","D. Dedicated circuit with failover"],"answer":1,"explain":"Site-to-Site VPN provides cost-effective connectivity sufficient for non-production environments."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A financial institution requires sub-millisecond latency for trading. Which connectivity option guarantees this?","options":["A. Site-to-Site VPN","B. Direct Connect with collocation","C. VPC endpoints","D. CloudFront edge locations"],"answer":1,"explain":"Direct Connect with collocation provides dedicated, low-latency connectivity for ultra-low-latency applications."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company needs transit connectivity between multiple on-premises locations through AWS. What pattern accomplishes this?","options":["A. Site-to-Site VPN hub at on-premises","B. Transit Gateway with multiple VPN attachments","C. VPC peering between offices","D. Direct Connect to each office"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit Gateway hub-and-spoke design enables on-premises locations to communicate through AWS."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company must extend existing VPC CIDR when space is nearly exhausted. How while maintaining instances?","options":["A. Migrate to new larger VPC","B. Add secondary CIDR blocks to VPC","C. Request larger CIDR from AWS","D. Split instances across new VPCs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Secondary CIDR blocks expand address space without instance migration."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A SaaS provider requires multi-tenant architecture with customer isolation. What design achieves this?","options":["A. Single VPC with customer security groups","B. Separate VPCs per customer with Transit Gateway","C. Shared VPC with subnets per customer","D. Overlapping CIDR blocks with NAT"],"answer":1,"explain":"Separate VPCs per tenant with Transit Gateway routing provides complete network isolation."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company needs redundant connectivity across multiple carriers. What is minimum Direct Connect configuration?","options":["A. Single connection with LAG","B. Multiple connections across diverse LOAs and carriers","C. Single connection with LAG in same location","D. Backup VPN on separate connection"],"answer":1,"explain":"Diverse Direct Connect connections across different AWS locations and carriers provide true redundancy."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company must isolate production and non-production at network layer. What design is best?","options":["A. Use IAM policies only","B. Separate VPCs with Transit Gateway and selective routing","C. Separate subnets in same VPC","D. Security groups only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Separate VPCs with Transit Gateway provide network-layer isolation while enabling controlled communication."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company plans VPC for 1000 to 100,000 IP growth. What CIDR is appropriate?","options":["A. 10.0.0.0/24","B. 10.0.0.0/18","C. 10.0.0.0/16","D. 10.0.0.0/8"],"answer":3,"explain":"/8 (16.7M addresses) accommodates growth with room for future scaling."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A multi-account organization needs centralized egress through Security Hub VPC. What architecture enables this?","options":["A. Transit Gateway with central egress subnet","B. VPC peering to security hub","C. Direct Connect to security hub","D. NAT Gateway in each VPC"],"answer":0,"explain":"Transit Gateway hub-and-spoke with central security VPC containing NAT Gateway enables consolidated egress."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company requires gradual on-premises to cloud migration. What hybrid architecture supports this?","options":["A. VPN only for security","B. Direct Connect with load sharing between on-premises and cloud","C. Separate on-premises and cloud networks","D. Cloud-only network"],"answer":1,"explain":"Direct Connect with load sharing allows gradual traffic migration from on-premises to cloud."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A global company needs multiple independent regional data centers. What topology is recommended?","options":["A. Full mesh VPC peering","B. Regional hubs with Transit Gateway and inter-regional peering","C. Single global VPC","D. No interconnection between regions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Regional Transit Gateways with inter-region peering support independent operations while enabling selective communication."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with 5 offices needs low-latency connectivity to AWS. What is most cost-effective?","options":["A. Direct Connect from each office","B. Site-to-Site VPN from each office with Transit Gateway","C. Direct Connect from central office only","D. Dedicated LANs between offices"],"answer":1,"explain":"Site-to-Site VPN provides cost-effective connectivity; Transit Gateway centralizes routing."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A startup requires rapid VPC design for 50 instances across 2 AZs. What minimum subnet architecture ensures flexibility?","options":["A. One subnet per AZ","B. One public and one private per AZ","C. One public, private, protected per AZ","D. Based on growth projections only"],"answer":2,"explain":"Three-tier architecture in each AZ provides web, app, database isolation from the start."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An organization must meet GDPR data residency. What VPC design achieves this?","options":["A. Single global VPC","B. VPCs in specific regions per requirement","C. Shared VPC across regions","D. CloudFront with regional caches"],"answer":1,"explain":"Regional VPCs ensure data remains in specified geographies meeting compliance requirements."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements hybrid network with Transit Gateway. What advantage over VPC peering?","options":["A. Transit Gateway provides lower latency","B. Eliminates need for route tables","C. One attachment per VPC replaces full mesh peering connections","D. Less expensive per GB"],"answer":2,"explain":"Transit Gateway hub-and-spoke replaces n*(n-1)/2 peering connections with n attachments."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company requires HA while minimizing inter-AZ data transfer costs. What architecture achieves this?","options":["A. Single AZ deployment","B. Sticky sessions within AZ with load balancer","C. Compute distributed across AZs with minimal cross-AZ replication","D. All traffic through single AZ"],"answer":2,"explain":"Compute distributed per AZ with minimal cross-AZ data replication reduces costs while maintaining HA."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A financial services firm requires three-tier architecture with separate zones. How many route tables minimum?","options":["A. One for all subnets","B. One per tier (3 total)","C. One per tier per AZ","D. Determined by compliance only"],"answer":2,"explain":"Each tier requires separate routing per AZ; one route table per tier per AZ."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company designs VPC endpoints for S3 cost optimization. Which endpoint type is preferred?","options":["A. Interface endpoint with NLB","B. Gateway endpoint","C. Both equally effective","D. Interface endpoint always"],"answer":1,"explain":"Gateway endpoints for S3 bypass NAT Gateway, saving data transfer costs."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A startup must quickly scale from 1000 to 10000 instances. What CIDR strategy enables this?","options":["A. Minimal /28 CIDR","B. Use secondary CIDR when primary is wrong","C. Plan primary and secondary CIDR ranges hierarchically","D. Request new VPC each time"],"answer":2,"explain":"Hierarchical CIDR planning with reserved secondary ranges avoids future redesigns."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing Client VPN realizes they need access to on-premises resources. What configuration is required?","options":["A. VPN endpoint only","B. Client configuration with route to on-premises","C. VPN endpoint, hybrid connectivity route, and client auth rules","D. Direct tunneling"],"answer":2,"explain":"Client VPN reaching on-premises requires hybrid connectivity, routes, and client auth rules."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with offices in 5 cities needs global connectivity. What design minimizes complexity?","options":["A. Direct Connect from each office","B. Site-to-Site VPN to Transit Gateway hub","C. VPN hub at central office","D. Dedicated LANs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit Gateway hub enables scalable connectivity across distributed offices."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company requires disaster recovery with sub-minute RTO. What architecture is required?","options":["A. Active-passive with hourly recovery","B. Active-active across regions with real-time replication","C. Periodic backups","D. Single region standby"],"answer":1,"explain":"Sub-minute RTO requires active-active across regions with continuous replication."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company plans network supporting 256 subnets for complex organization. What VPC CIDR is needed?","options":["A. 10.0.0.0/24","B. 10.0.0.0/20","C. 10.0.0.0/16","D. 10.0.0.0/12"],"answer":2,"explain":"/16 provides 256 possible /24 subnets accommodating complex organizational structure."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company requires network design supporting customer segmentation per facility. What minimum design?","options":["A. Public VPC with encryption","B. Private subnets with internet access","C. Isolated private subnets per facility with restricted egress and audit logging","D. Shared subnets across facilities"],"answer":2,"explain":"Customer isolation requires isolated subnets per facility with private connectivity and comprehensive audit."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An organization needs VPC endpoint service for customers. What must be configured?","options":["A. Producer service endpoint in provider account","B. Consumer VPC creates interface endpoint","C. Producer service endpoint AND consumer creates interface endpoint","D. VPC peering to service"],"answer":2,"explain":"Producer creates PrivateLink service endpoint; consumers create interface endpoints."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing PrivateLink for internal services realizes they forgot a critical component. What is essential?","options":["A. Consumer security group configuration","B. Producer service network load balancer","C. Producer service endpoint AND consumer interface endpoint","D. Route 53 health checks"],"answer":2,"explain":"PrivateLink requires producer-side service endpoint with NLB and consumer-side interface endpoint."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company configuring Transit Gateway realizes accounts cannot reach shared services. What configuration is required?","options":["A. VPC peering instead of Transit Gateway","B. Shared services VPC with Transit Gateway attachment and route table entries in spokes","C. Direct VPN to each spoke","D. Transit Gateway doesn't support shared services"],"answer":1,"explain":"Spoke route tables must have entries pointing to shared services VPC via Transit Gateway."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A startup designing network for rapid growth requires flexibility. What VPC CIDR strategy enables this?","options":["A. Minimal /28 CIDR","B. Use secondary blocks when primary sizing is wrong","C. Plan primary and secondary ranges hierarchically from start","D. Request new VPC each time"],"answer":2,"explain":"Hierarchical planning with reserved secondary CIDR ranges prevents future redesigns."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company designing VPC endpoint service for customers must understand what consumer does. What is their action?","options":["A. Request access from provider","B. Create interface endpoint to connect to provider's PrivateLink service","C. Establish VPC peering","D. Configure NAT to service IP"],"answer":1,"explain":"Consumers create interface endpoints in their VPCs connecting to provider's PrivateLink service."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing global networking realizes they need different behaviors per region. What allows this?","options":["A. Single transit gateway globally","B. Identical configurations everywhere","C. Regional transit gateways with inter-region peering and region-specific routing","D. Separate networks without connectivity"],"answer":2,"explain":"Regional Transit Gateways enable region-specific routing while inter-region peering maintains global connectivity."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing multi-region fails to configure inter-region routes. What breaks connectivity?","options":["A. Transit Gateway peering attachment is created","B. Peering is accepted","C. Route table entries in both regions pointing to peering connection are missing","D. Internet Gateway attachment"],"answer":2,"explain":"Inter-region peering requires explicit route table entries in both regions."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company initializing VPC design for multi-tier application across 8 AZs and 2 regions. Subnet count needed?","options":["A. One subnet per AZ","B. Two subnets per AZ (public/private)","C. Three subnets per AZ (public/private/protected)","D. Three subnets per AZ per region minimum"],"answer":3,"explain":"3 tiers × 8 AZs × 2 regions = 48 subnets minimum for proper tier isolation."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company needing to connect 100 branch offices through AWS must choose scalable architecture. What breaks full mesh?","options":["A. VPC peering between all branches","B. Site-to-Site VPN from each to AWS","C. 100 branch-to-branch peering connections (4,950 possible relationships)","D. Transit Gateway with 100 VPN attachments"],"answer":2,"explain":"Full mesh between 100 branches = 4,950 peering connections; Transit Gateway hub (one per branch) is vastly more efficient."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing compliance-driven network segmentation for internet-facing, application, database tiers. What else is forgotten?","options":["A. Protecting the internet-facing tier","B. Encrypting traffic between tiers","C. Management tier network for admin access with separate restricted connectivity","D. Using different VPCs"],"answer":2,"explain":"Modern segmentation includes separate management tier with restricted access for admin functions."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with global offices implementing Direct Connect realizes they forgot redundancy element. What is critical?","options":["A. One connection per region","B. LAG within single location","C. Multiple connections across diverse AWS locations AND carriers","D. VPN backup only"],"answer":2,"explain":"True redundancy requires geographically diverse Direct Connect connections across different carriers."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company extending VPC architecture to support 10,000 instances realizes subnet planning was insufficient. What causes problem?","options":["A. CIDR block is too small","B. Using too many small subnets","C. Lack of hierarchical growth planning with secondary CIDR blocks","D. Instances cannot be added to VPC"],"answer":2,"explain":"Lack of growth planning requires major redesign; reserved secondary CIDR blocks prevent this."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures Customer Gateway for VPN but BGP fails. Logs show ASN mismatch. What is issue?","options":["A. Virtual Gateway and Customer Gateway have different BGP AS numbers","B. VPN tunnel is DOWN","C. Border router does not support BGP","D. Route table does not have BGP routes"],"answer":0,"explain":"BGP sessions require matching ASN configuration; mismatches prevent peer establishment."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network engineer configures Direct Connect VIF but routes missing despite VIF UP. What is needed?","options":["A. Routes automatically added by AWS","B. Routes must be manually added or propagated via BGP","C. Routes appear after BGP session","D. Wait 15 minutes for automatic routing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Routes can be propagated automatically via BGP or manually entered depending on configuration."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company implements Client VPN for split tunnel to reduce bandwidth. What controls this?","options":["A. Endpoint route table filtering","B. Authentication rules","C. Endpoint settings for client routes","D. Security group rules on endpoint"],"answer":2,"explain":"Client VPN split tunnel configured via endpoint settings specifying routes through VPN."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network architect implements VPC peering. Traffic fails despite security groups allowing. What is missing?","options":["A. Peering connection acceptance","B. Route table entries on BOTH VPCs pointing to peering connection","C. Network ACL rules","D. Internet Gateway attachment"],"answer":1,"explain":"Both sides of VPC peering require route table entries; missing routes prevent traffic."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company configures multiple Direct Connect VIFs on one connection. How are they logically separated?","options":["A. Separate physical ports","B. VLAN tagging on the same port","C. BGP AS path","D. Separate IP addresses"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multiple VIFs on one Direct Connect connection separated via VLAN tags."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A multinational financial services company operates across 15 AWS regions and needs to implement a CIDR strategy for 50 VPCs. The company requires no overlapping address spaces and must support future growth to 200 VPCs. Which CIDR scheme and planning approach best accommodates this requirement while maintaining clean routing?","options":["A. Use a /8 block globally and subdivide into /18 per region with secondary blocks reserved","B. Use /16 for each region independently with no planning for growth","C. Use /24 blocks to maximize subnets per VPC","D. Use overlapping blocks and rely on NAT to prevent conflicts"],"answer":0,"explain":"A /8 provides 16.7M addresses, allowing /18 per region (262k each) with growth capacity. Hierarchical planning with reserved secondary blocks is essential for multi-region scaling."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network engineer enables route propagation from Direct Connect but static routes override propagated. What causes?","options":["A. Route propagation is disabled","B. Static routes have higher priority than propagated routes","C. BGP advertisements are incorrect","D. VPN routes are preferred"],"answer":1,"explain":"Static route table entries always take precedence over propagated dynamic routes."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company implements Client VPN but users cannot access resources. What is missing?","options":["A. Mutual TLS authentication","B. Target network associations and authorization rules","C. SAML authentication","D. Route 53 DNS"],"answer":1,"explain":"Client VPN requires target network associations and authorization rules for resource access."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network architect configures Direct Connect LAG for bandwidth aggregation. What is minimum required?","options":["A. Two connections","B. One connection","C. Four connections","D. Flexible count"],"answer":0,"explain":"LAG requires minimum 2 connections to aggregate bandwidth and provide redundancy."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company configures VPN IPSec tunnels but observes packet loss. MTU is 1500. What causes?","options":["A. BGP session flapping","B. MTU size mismatch","C. IPSec encryption overhead exceeds MTU causing fragmentation","D. BGP route conflicts"],"answer":2,"explain":"IPSec encryption adds overhead; if tunnel MTU exceeds underlying link MTU, fragmentation occurs."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network engineer implements Transit Gateway with attachments but traffic between fails. What is misconfigured?","options":["A. Transit Gateway route table lacks required routes","B. Transit Gateway is DOWN","C. Attachments not propagating routes","D. Attachment association is invalid"],"answer":0,"explain":"Transit Gateway requires explicit route table entries; traffic only flows with defined routes."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company establishes Direct Connect but experiences latency spikes. What configuration is missing?","options":["A. Enabling jumbo frames","B. Multiple VIFs for load distribution","C. Increasing bandwidth","D. VPN as backup"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multiple VIFs across diverse locations provide redundancy and load balancing."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network engineer configures BGP route propagation but routes don't appear. BGP is UP. What is issue?","options":["A. BGP ASN conflicts","B. VPN route propagation not enabled on route table","C. Security group blocking BGP","D. VPN tunnel is DOWN"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route propagation must be explicitly enabled on the route table."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company deploys Client VPN but users cannot access resources in private subnet. What is issue?","options":["A. Mutual TLS authentication","B. Target network association missing or authorization rules blocking","C. SAML authentication failure","D. Route 53 DNS issues"],"answer":1,"explain":"Client VPN requires target associations and authorization rules."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company configures BGP route propagation but traffic prefers VPN over Direct Connect during DX maintenance. How is this controlled?","options":["A. BGP local preference values","B. AS path prepending","C. Route table prioritization","D. Disable BGP on Direct Connect"],"answer":0,"explain":"BGP local preference controls path selection."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company configures NAT Gateway in private subnet but instances cannot reach internet. What is the flaw?","options":["A. NAT Gateway cannot be in private subnets","B. NAT Gateway must be in public subnet with Elastic IP","C. NAT Gateway requires security group","D. Requires Internet Gateway attachment"],"answer":1,"explain":"NAT Gateways must reside in public subnets with Elastic IP."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network engineer needs to enable IPv6 egress for private subnet. What component is required?","options":["A. Egress-only Internet Gateway with route table entry","B. NAT Gateway with IPv6","C. VPN endpoint for IPv6","D. Route 53 resolver"],"answer":0,"explain":"Egress-only IGWs enable IPv6 instances to reach internet while preventing inbound."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company requires VPN redundancy with automatic failover. How should connections be configured?","options":["A. Single connection with redundant tunnels","B. Multiple connections to separate Customer Gateways with dynamic routing","C. Multiple connections with identical BGP weights","D. Single connection with load balancing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multiple VPN connections to separate Customer Gateways enable automatic failover."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company configures multiple Direct Connect VIFs. How are they separated?","options":["A. Separate physical ports","B. VLAN tagging for logical separation","C. BGP AS path","D. IP addresses"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multiple VIFs on one connection separated via VLAN tags."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network engineer establishes Direct Connect with public VIF but cannot access S3 public IP. What is configured?","options":["A. S3 IPs not advertised on public VIF","B. AWS does not advertise S3 addresses","C. Public VIF advertises S3 but route table entry missing","D. S3 requires interface endpoint"],"answer":2,"explain":"Public VIF advertises AWS service IPs but route table entry required."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company implements Client VPN with mutual TLS. What client-side configuration is required?","options":["A. Only client certificate","B. Client certificate and private key","C. Client certificate, private key, and CA certificate","D. CA certificate only"],"answer":2,"explain":"Mutual TLS requires client certificate, private key, and CA certificate."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network architect implements VPC peering across 10 VPCs. What is the primary limitation?","options":["A. VPC peering cannot handle 10 VPCs","B. Full mesh requires 45 peering connections; Transit Gateway is better","C. All VPCs must be in same region","D. CIDR blocks must be identical"],"answer":1,"explain":"10 VPCs full mesh = 45 connections; Transit Gateway simplifies to one attachment per VPC."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company configures backup VPN alongside Direct Connect. How should preference be configured?","options":["A. Equal weighting in route table","B. BGP local preference with DX preferred","C. VPN as primary, DX as backup","D. Load balancing between both"],"answer":1,"explain":"BGP local preference makes Direct Connect preferred; VPN serves as backup."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company configures Client VPN with SAML 2.0. What authentication provides most flexibility?","options":["A. Mutual TLS only","B. SAML 2.0 federated authentication","C. RADIUS authentication","D. Active Directory only"],"answer":1,"explain":"SAML 2.0 enables federated authentication with corporate identity providers."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Network engineer implements Transit Gateway with attachments. Traffic between spokes fails. What is missing?","options":["A. Transit Gateway route table entries or route propagation","B. Attachments must be AVAILABLE","C. BGP configuration","D. Internet Gateway"],"answer":0,"explain":"Transit Gateway requires explicit route table entries or propagation."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company establishes shared services VPC via Transit Gateway. What configuration is required?","options":["A. Peering between spoke and shared services only","B. Shared services VPC attachment with route table entries in spokes","C. VPN connections only","D. VPC peering to shared services"],"answer":1,"explain":"Shared services require Transit Gateway attachment and route table entries."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"Company configures Virtual Private Gateway with route propagation but static routes override BGP. Why?","options":["A. BGP is broken","B. Static routes always have higher priority than propagated routes","C. BGP routes are preferred","D. VGW is misconfigured"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS routing always prefers static routes over propagated routes."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Network team analyzes VPC Flow Logs and identifies unauthorized traffic. What must be verified before blocking?","options":["A. Source and destination IPs are actually unauthorized","B. Flow log format is correct","C. CloudWatch retention is sufficient","D. Flow Logs enabled on all ENIs"],"answer":0,"explain":"Flow Log analysis should verify IPs are actually unauthorized before firewall implementation."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Network team enables subnet-level Flow Logs. What is a key limitation?","options":["A. Misses individual instance traffic","B. Cannot differentiate between instances in the subnet","C. Less detailed format","D. More expensive"],"answer":1,"explain":"Subnet-level Flow Logs cannot attribute traffic to specific ENIs."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Company uses Reachability Analyzer and gets REACHABLE. Why might application connection still fail?","options":["A. Layer 4 connectivity exists but application auth/TLS may fail","B. RDS security group changed after test","C. Instance security group modified","D. Reachability Analyzer is inaccurate"],"answer":0,"explain":"Reachability Analyzer confirms layer 3/4; application-layer failures are not detected."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Company must monitor egress bandwidth for cost control. What metric provides per-instance visibility?","options":["A. NetworkIn and NetworkOut total","B. BytesSentToDestination from ALB","C. NetworkPacketsOut only","D. EC2 NetworkBytesOut per instance"],"answer":3,"explain":"EC2 NetworkBytesOut provides per-instance egress metrics for cost analysis."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Network engineer enables traffic mirroring for encryption monitoring. Where is filter applied?","options":["A. On source ENI egress filter","B. On both source and destination ENIs","C. On mirror target network interface","D. On traffic mirror session target"],"answer":0,"explain":"Traffic Mirror filters applied at the source ENI."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Company requires DNS monitoring for security. What is the best architecture?","options":["A. Route 53 Resolver query logging to CloudWatch","B. VPC Flow Logs for port 53","C. CloudWatch Application Insights","D. Traffic Mirroring to analyzer"],"answer":0,"explain":"Route 53 Resolver query logging enables DNS analysis for security."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Network team observes asymmetric routing. What diagnostic approach identifies the cause?","options":["A. Increase TTL in Route 53","B. Analyze routing tables and BGP advertisements on both sides","C. Enable VPC Flow Logs on all subnets","D. Increase Direct Connect bandwidth"],"answer":1,"explain":"Asymmetric routing stems from misaligned routing policies."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Company implements Network Access Analyzer. What does it NOT evaluate?","options":["A. Layer 7 application traffic patterns","B. Network configuration paths","C. Encryption standards compliance","D. BGP propagation timing"],"answer":0,"explain":"Network Access Analyzer checks configurations; doesn't inspect application traffic."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Network engineer troubleshoots inter-AZ latency. What metric approach is most direct?","options":["A. NetworkLatency CloudWatch metric","B. RTT measurements via ping/TCP","C. VPC Flow Logs analysis","D. Direct Connect connection latency"],"answer":1,"explain":"RTT measurements directly measure inter-AZ latency."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Company monitors NAT Gateway metrics observing high connection count. What metric indicates port exhaustion?","options":["A. BytesOutToDestination","B. ConnectionCount metric","C. PacketsDropped","D. ErrorPortAllocation metric"],"answer":3,"explain":"ErrorPortAllocation metric indicates NAT Gateway port exhaustion."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Company deploys Traffic Mirroring to network appliance. What throughput limitation exists?","options":["A. Unlimited","B. Limited to source ENI performance","C. Limited by mirror target capacity","D. Limited to 10 Gbps aggregate"],"answer":2,"explain":"Mirror target capacity is the throughput bottleneck."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Network team analyzes VPC Flow Logs for baseline patterns. What identifies anomalies?","options":["A. Bytes count trending","B. Packet count trending","C. Both bytes and packets compared against historical baselines","D. Flow record count"],"answer":2,"explain":"Both metrics compared against baselines reveal unusual patterns."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Company monitors Direct Connect metrics but notices missing metrics. Why?","options":["A. Not available for Direct Connect","B. CloudWatch agent must be installed","C. Metrics require explicit enablement","D. Only at LOA level"],"answer":2,"explain":"Direct Connect metrics require explicit monitoring enablement."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Network engineer monitors traffic mirroring logs and observes duplicate packets. Why?","options":["A. Mirroring filter capturing duplicates","B. Source ENI sending duplicates","C. Multiple mirror sessions capturing same traffic","D. Mirror target echoing packets"],"answer":2,"explain":"Overlapping traffic mirror sessions can capture same traffic."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Company implements Network Access Analyzer with warnings about internet reachability. What is appropriate first response?","options":["A. Immediately block all inbound access","B. Verify if access is intentional before remediation","C. Disable instance","D. Enable Shield Advanced"],"answer":1,"explain":"NAA findings require validation; not all internet-reachable instances are security risks."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"Network team monitors Direct Connect with decreasing throughput. What diagnostic approach confirms congestion location?","options":["A. AWS CloudWatch metrics only","B. On-premises interface statistics only","C. Both AWS and on-premises metrics comparison","D. BGP timer analysis"],"answer":2,"explain":"Comprehensive diagnostics compare metrics from both sides."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company implements AWS Network Firewall but observes excessive blocking. What immediate action should be taken?","options":["A. Disable the firewall","B. Analyze blocked logs and refine rules","C. Switch to security groups","D. Increase rule priorities"],"answer":1,"explain":"Analyze logs to identify false positives and refine rules."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Financial services company configures Network Firewall for intrusion detection. What rule type is effective?","options":["A. Stateless rules","B. Domain list rules","C. Stateful rules with IDS/IPS signatures","D. Application layer only"],"answer":2,"explain":"Stateful rules with IDS/IPS signatures detect sophisticated attacks."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company uses WAF to protect APIs. SQL injection still bypasses. What additional layer is needed?","options":["A. More WAF rules","B. Network Firewall stateless","C. Application-layer input validation","D. Shield Advanced"],"answer":2,"explain":"Defense-in-depth requires application-layer protections."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company configures Network Firewall rule groups with overlapping rules. Which group is evaluated first?","options":["A. First created","B. Lowest priority number","C. Most specific domains","D. In parallel"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rule groups evaluated sequentially by priority."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Organization implements stateful Network Firewall rules for port scanning prevention. What pattern is detected?","options":["A. Multiple ports on same destination","B. High packet rates","C. Unestablished TCP connections","D. All equally"],"answer":2,"explain":"Stateful rules detect multiple unestablished connections."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company requires Network Firewall to block all except approved services. What approach is efficient?","options":["A. Allow rules for each service","B. Deny rules for unapproved","C. Managed rules","D. Domain list with allowlist"],"answer":3,"explain":"Domain list with allowlist provides efficient control."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Healthcare provider requires least-privilege vendor access. Vendor requests 0.0.0.0/8 range. What is appropriate?","options":["A. Grant request","B. Require specific IPs","C. Use /24 compromise","D. Separate security group"],"answer":1,"explain":"Least-privilege requires specific IP ranges."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company analyzes security group rules. Rule allows all traffic from another security group. When is this risky?","options":["A. If in same VPC","B. If group attached to compromised instances","C. If uses all ports","D. If created last month"],"answer":1,"explain":"Risk depends on security of referenced group."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Network engineer implements Network Firewall for production. What is best practice for testing?","options":["A. Enable all rules immediately","B. Use alert action initially then enforce","C. Test off-hours only","D. Disable real-time blocking"],"answer":1,"explain":"Alert action allows validation without blocking."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company requires DDoS protection for encrypted traffic. What service provides this?","options":["A. WAF with encrypted inspection","B. Shield Advanced at perimeter","C. Network Firewall with TLS","D. Not possible"],"answer":1,"explain":"Shield Advanced protects at perimeter before decryption."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Network administrator discovers security group allowing 0.0.0.0/0 on port 3306. How to remediate?","options":["A. Change to app server security group","B. Add DENY rule","C. Use Network ACL","D. Add encryption"],"answer":0,"explain":"Restrict port 3306 to application servers only."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company uses WAF for API protection but needs testing exemptions. How?","options":["A. Disable WAF","B. IP-based or header-based rule exemptions","C. Whitelist testing network","D. Separate policy"],"answer":1,"explain":"WAF supports IP and header-based exemptions."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company implements Network Firewall with domain-based blocking. Attacker uses IP-based bypass. What is needed?","options":["A. More domain rules","B. IP-based rules blocking destinations","C. WAF IP reputation","D. Security groups"],"answer":1,"explain":"Block both domain names and IPs for complete protection."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Financial services company configures Shield Advanced during DDoS attack. What does DRT provide?","options":["A. Automatic mitigation","B. 24/7 expert support and cost protection","C. DNS mitigation only","D. Firewall configuration"],"answer":1,"explain":"DRT provides expert guidance and cost protection."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company implements Firewall Manager policies but sees inconsistent enforcement across regions. Why?","options":["A. Not applied globally","B. Policies are regional","C. Accounts not tagged","D. Evaluation is async"],"answer":0,"explain":"Firewall Manager policies are regional by design."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company requires Network Firewall to detect SQL injection. What inspection is required?","options":["A. Domain inspection only","B. IP reputation lists","C. Stateful rules with IDS/IPS signatures","D. Network ACL rules"],"answer":2,"explain":"SQL injection detection requires stateful inspection."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company implements Network Firewall rule groups. How should they be organized?","options":["A. By direction","B. By protocol","C. By business function","D. Randomly"],"answer":2,"explain":"Organize by business function for maintainability."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company implements Network Firewall with SSL/TLS inspection. What is the limitation?","options":["A. Cannot inspect encrypted","B. Not supported by Firewall","C. Requires certificate pinning disabled","D. Too much overhead"],"answer":2,"explain":"TLS inspection limited by application certificate pinning."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Company uses WAF on ALB for application protection. Why might attacks still pass?","options":["A. WAF is ineffective","B. Attacks exploit application logic not covered by network rules","C. Switch to security groups","D. Disable ALB security groups"],"answer":1,"explain":"Defense-in-depth requires application-layer protections."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"Network security architect designs protection for critical web application. What components are required?","options":["A. WAF only","B. Network Firewall only","C. Shield + Network Firewall + WAF + security groups","D. Security groups only"],"answer":2,"explain":"Defense-in-depth requires multiple layers."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company configures Transit Gateway multi-region peering. What is essential?","options":["A. Attachment only","B. Peering attachment and route tables in both regions","C. No additional config","D. Separate gateways"],"answer":0,"explain":"Inter-region peering requires attachment and route table entries."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An enterprise with 8 AWS accounts across 3 regions implements a hub-and-spoke topology using Transit Gateway. The architecture must support transitive routing between spokes, centralized security scanning, and isolated DNS zones per customer. Which additional component is critical for DNS isolation?","options":["A. Route 53 public hosted zones in the hub","B. Route 53 Resolver endpoints in the hub with conditional forwarding rules per spoke","C. CloudFront distributions for DNS caching","D. VPC Flow Logs for DNS tracking"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 Resolver with inbound/outbound endpoints and conditional forwarding enables isolated DNS resolution per VPC while maintaining hybrid connectivity."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A healthcare organization implementing IPv6 in AWS for compliance requires egress-only internet access for medical devices while maintaining IPv4 for legacy systems. What must be configured for dual-stack IPv6 functionality without internet ingress?","options":["A. Assign IPv6 CIDR to VPC and create Internet Gateway","B. Assign IPv6 CIDR to VPC/subnets, create Egress-Only Internet Gateway, and update route tables","C. Use NAT64 with Route 53","D. Create IPv6-only security groups"],"answer":1,"explain":"Egress-Only Internet Gateway (EIGW) allows outbound IPv6 while blocking ingress, essential for compliance-driven environments requiring uni-directional traffic."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A trading firm requires sub-millisecond latency for market data feeds from London data center to AWS. The connection must support 10 Gbps with automatic failover to secondary connection if primary fails. Which architecture combines these requirements optimally?","options":["A. Two Site-to-Site VPNs with equal-cost multi-path routing","B. Two Direct Connect Virtual Interfaces in LAG with automatic failover to third DX connection in different location","C. Single Direct Connect with VPN backup","D. Three overlapping VPN connections with health checks"],"answer":1,"explain":"LAG provides link aggregation with automatic failover. Diverse physical connections across different AWS DX locations ensure true redundancy for latency-sensitive trading."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A SaaS platform with 100 enterprise customers needs to expose internal microservices securely without internet exposure. Customers should access via their own VPCs with private endpoints. Which PrivateLink configuration is required?","options":["A. Gateway endpoints for each customer VPC","B. Producer service endpoint with Network Load Balancer, consumers create interface endpoints in their VPCs","C. VPC peering between each customer and producer","D. Shared VPC with customer subnets"],"answer":1,"explain":"PrivateLink (Interface Endpoints) provides secure, private service exposure. Producer creates service endpoint backed by NLB; consumers create endpoints to connect."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An organization implementing AWS Cloud WAN must manage networks across 12 on-premises locations, 5 AWS regions, and 20 AWS accounts. What core benefit of Cloud WAN enables centralized policy-based routing for this complex topology?","options":["A. Automatic CIDR resolution","B. Centralized network policy engine with intent-based routing policies across all attachments","C. Elimination of Transit Gateway requirement","D. Automatic failover without configuration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cloud WAN's policy engine enables intent-based routing (e.g., 'route all production traffic through DX'), centralized management of complex multi-account, multi-region topologies."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A multinational corporation requires that customer data never leaves specific regions for compliance (GDPR for EU, HIPAA for US). VPC design must prevent accidental cross-region data flow. What architectural pattern enforces this at the network layer?","options":["A. Regional VPCs with no inter-region Transit Gateway peering","B. Regional VPCs with Transit Gateway but routes blocked via Transit Gateway route tables","C. Single global VPC with subnets per region","D. Rely on application-layer logic to prevent cross-region traffic"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit Gateway route tables can explicitly block inter-region propagation. Regional isolation at network layer prevents accidental compliance violations."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company operating 100 branch offices through AWS Transit Gateway realizes that all spoke-to-spoke communication must route through the hub, creating bottlenecks. They want some branches to communicate directly. What Transit Gateway feature enables direct spoke-to-spoke communication?","options":["A. Transit Gateway multicast","B. Transit Gateway peering between spokes","C. Transit Gateway route tables with dynamic routing between spokes","D. AWS Transit Gateway does not support spoke-to-spoke; redesign required"],"answer":2,"explain":"Transit Gateway route tables can propagate routes between spokes selectively. Spokes can be configured to reach each other without routing through hub, reducing latency."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A retailer implementing a three-tier DMZ requires complete network segmentation: web tier (public), app tier (private), database tier (isolated). Additionally, they need a management tier for admin access with highly restricted connectivity. How many route tables minimum are needed per AZ?","options":["A. One route table for all tiers","B. Three route tables (one per tier)","C. Four route tables (one per tier plus management)","D. Determined by the number of instances"],"answer":2,"explain":"Management tier requires separate route table with restricted egress. Each tier requires distinct routing: web→IGW, app→NAT, db→none, mgmt→restricted endpoint."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company extending its VPC from /16 to accommodate 50,000 instances realizes they've already used the entire primary CIDR block. They cannot recreate the VPC without major downtime. What feature allows adding IP space while keeping existing instances running?","options":["A. Secondary CIDR blocks on the VPC","B. NAT Gateway expansion","C. Request larger CIDR from AWS","D. Migrate to new VPC immediately"],"answer":0,"explain":"Secondary CIDR blocks (up to 5) can be added to existing VPCs without affecting running instances. New subnets can be created from secondary blocks without migration."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A global SaaS platform must implement complete multi-tenancy with customer VPC isolation, preventing any possibility of cross-customer traffic. They also need a shared centralized service for logging and DLP. Which architecture best achieves both isolation and centralized services?","options":["A. Single VPC with customer security groups","B. Separate VPCs per customer with Transit Gateway to shared services VPC only, no cross-customer routes","C. Overlapping CIDR blocks with NAT","D. Shared VPC with customer-specific subnets"],"answer":1,"explain":"Separate VPCs per customer with Transit Gateway star topology (only to services hub) enforces isolation while allowing centralized services. Explicit route table entries prevent cross-customer communication."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A manufacturing company operates factories in 5 countries and needs to consolidate all on-premises locations through AWS with centralized egress and security scanning. The primary requirement is low latency to nearest AWS region per factory. Which hybrid architecture is most efficient?","options":["A. Direct Connect from each factory to nearest AWS region","B. Site-to-Site VPN from each factory to Central Transit Gateway hub with Express Route for primary locations","C. Site-to-Site VPN to regional hubs + Transit Gateway inter-region peering, with centralized egress VPC","D. Dedicated WAN connecting all factories to single AWS region"],"answer":2,"explain":"Regional Transit Gateway hubs with inter-region peering provide local connectivity to nearest region while centralizing security. Spoke route tables direct all egress through security hub."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements VPC peering between its production and development VPCs for controlled resource sharing. Developers accidentally route traffic meant for production peer to a third VPC through transitive routing. What architecture prevents this design flaw?","options":["A. Use VPC Flow Logs to detect transitive routing","B. Implement Transit Gateway to replace VPC peering with explicit, controlled routing","C. Rely on security groups to block transitive traffic","D. VPC peering inherently prevents transitive routing; reconfigure route tables"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC peering is non-transitive by design. Transit Gateway with explicit route tables provides more granular control over multi-VPC communication patterns."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A financial institution requires disaster recovery across regions with sub-minute RTO and must minimize replication latency to maximize throughput. Active-passive architecture is too slow. What minimum architecture achieves active-active across regions?","options":["A. Replicate snapshots hourly across regions","B. Active-active with DynamoDB global tables, Aurora global database, and real-time data replication via Kinesis","C. Backup VPC in secondary region with manual failover","D. Single region with AWS Backup"],"answer":1,"explain":"Active-active requires continuous bi-directional replication. DynamoDB global tables + Aurora global database + Kinesis provide sub-second replication for sub-minute RTO."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company planning gradual migration from on-premises to AWS needs hybrid architecture supporting incremental workload movement. They want to gradually shift load from on-premises to cloud without disrupting existing operations. What Direct Connect strategy enables this?","options":["A. Single Direct Connect with full capacity immediately","B. Direct Connect with load balancing/weighted routing allowing gradual traffic shift between on-premises and cloud","C. Multiple Direct Connects with equal-cost multi-path","D. Switch immediately when Direct Connect is ready"],"answer":1,"explain":"Weighted BGP routing policies on Direct Connect allow gradual traffic percentage shifts (10% cloud, 90% on-prem → 50/50 → full cloud migration) without cutover risk."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An organization with 15 AWS accounts across 4 regions implementing centralized logging and compliance monitoring needs to forward all logs and DLP alerts to a central account. What network design enables this egress concentration?","options":["A. NAT Gateway in each spoke VPC pointing to internet","B. Transit Gateway hub with centralized egress VPC containing NAT Gateway and security appliances, all spokes route external traffic through hub","C. VPC peering to central account","D. Separate VPN per spoke"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hub-and-spoke Transit Gateway architecture with central egress VPC provides single point for security scanning, logging, and compliance monitoring."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company operating multiple Direct Connect connections to AWS requires BGP redundancy with automatic failover. What must be configured on the Customer Gateway side to enable BGP-based failover between primary and backup DX connections?","options":["A. Configure identical BGP ASNs on both connections","B. Configure different BGP ASNs with different local preference values to force failover path selection","C. BGP failover happens automatically without configuration","D. Use static routing instead of BGP"],"answer":1,"explain":"BGP local preference attribute controls failover. Primary connection configured with higher local preference; backup with lower preference. On failure, traffic automatically reroutes."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A telco implementing Direct Connect LAG (Link Aggregation Group) across 4 physical connections to AWS realizes that one physical connection to a different AWS location went down. Does LAG failover automatically handle this, and what should be configured for true redundancy?","options":["A. LAG automatically failovers; no additional configuration needed","B. LAG handles individual link failure but geographic failure requires secondary LAG at different location with BGP failover","C. LAG does not support geographic failover; switch to VPN","D. Configure additional LAG member connections"],"answer":1,"explain":"LAG protects against individual link failure but not AWS location failure. True geographic redundancy requires secondary LAG at different AWS DX location with BGP routing."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with Direct Connect and Site-to-Site VPN connections realizes that during DX maintenance windows, traffic should automatically fail over to VPN. Currently, no failover occurs. What routing configuration is required?","options":["A. VPN is always used first","B. Direct Connect virtual interfaces have lower BGP cost, VPN has higher cost; during DX failure, routes withdrawn and traffic fails over to VPN","C. Requires application-level health checks","D. Both paths carry equal load simultaneously"],"answer":1,"explain":"BGP configuration with lower AS-path for DX makes it preferred during normal operation. On DX virtual interface failure, routes are withdrawn and VPN takes over."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with on-premises Active Directory and AWS needs hybrid DNS where on-premises can resolve AWS Route 53 private hosted zones and AWS can resolve on-premises DNS. What Route 53 feature enables this bidirectional resolution?","options":["A. Route 53 public hosted zones","B. Route 53 Resolver with inbound endpoints (for on-prem→AWS) and outbound endpoints (for AWS→on-prem) with conditional forwarding rules","C. Route 53 health checks","D. CloudFront for DNS caching"],"answer":1,"explain":"Resolver inbound endpoints accept queries from on-premises for AWS hosted zones. Outbound endpoints forward AWS queries to on-premises DNS servers. Together, they enable bidirectional resolution."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An organization implementing Route 53 Resolver endpoints realizes they need to ensure DNS queries for *.internal domain automatically route to on-premises DNS servers while other queries resolve normally. What configuration is required?","options":["A. Create public hosted zone for *.internal","B. Outbound Resolver endpoint with conditional forwarding rule matching *.internal pattern to on-premises DNS IPs","C. Route 53 health checks on internal domains","D. VPC endpoint for on-premises DNS"],"answer":1,"explain":"Conditional forwarding rules on outbound Resolver endpoints enable pattern-based routing. Domains matching *.internal forward to on-premises; others resolve normally."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A global SaaS company requires sophisticated routing policies: directing users to nearest geographic region, with fallback to secondary region on primary failure, and weighted distribution for canary deployments. Which Route 53 policies must be combined?","options":["A. Geoproximity routing only","B. Geoproximity + failover + weighted routing policies combined in Route 53 Traffic Flow","C. Simple routing with application-side failover","D. Geolocation routing only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 Traffic Flow enables complex multi-policy routing. Geoproximity directs by location, failover handles primary failure, weighted routing enables canary deployments."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing DNSSEC with Route 53 requires signature validation to prevent DNS spoofing attacks on sensitive internal services. What must be configured for full DNSSEC chain validation?","options":["A. Enable DNSSEC signing on Route 53 hosted zone only","B. Enable DNSSEC signing on Route 53 + configure KSK (Key Signing Key) + validate DS records at parent zone","C. DNSSEC is automatic in Route 53","D. Use CloudFront for DNS security"],"answer":1,"explain":"DNSSEC requires signing (enabled in Route 53) plus KSK management and DS record configuration at parent zone to establish full chain of trust."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implementing Gateway Load Balancer for inline traffic inspection realizes that return traffic from the inspection appliance is not reaching clients. What is the most likely issue with the routing or configuration?","options":["A. GWLB target group health check failed","B. Asymmetric routing: traffic flows through GWLB but return traffic bypasses it due to route table configuration","C. Security group blocks return traffic","D. GWLB does not support bidirectional flow"],"answer":1,"explain":"GWLB requires symmetric routing. Forward and return traffic must both traverse the load balancer. Route tables must ensure return traffic also flows through GWLB to appliance and back to client."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures Site-to-Site VPN between on-premises and AWS. Tunnel comes up but traffic fails with asymmetric latency that appears unpredictable. BGP is not configured. What is the likely cause and solution?","options":["A. VPN encapsulation overhead; disable MTU","B. Asymmetric routing (forward path via VPN tunnel, return path via different route/internet); use BGP to enforce symmetric paths or static routing","C. VPN speed is inherently asymmetric","D. Requires application-level optimization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Without BGP or static routes preventing asymmetric paths, traffic can return via internet instead of VPN tunnel. BGP ensures symmetric path. Static routes on both sides enforce consistency."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements Network Load Balancer with TLS termination for east-west microservice communication between two VPCs. Encrypted traffic shows connection timeouts. What must be configured for NLB TLS?","options":["A. TLS version only","B. TLS certificates + cipher suites + target health checks for backend services with matching certificate validation","C. NLB automatically handles TLS","D. Application-level TLS configuration only"],"answer":1,"explain":"NLB TLS termination requires valid certificates, cipher suite configuration, and target health checks must validate backend TLS certificates. Mismatched validation causes connection failures."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company realizes that Client VPN endpoints can access VPC resources but cannot reach on-premises networks through the hybrid connectivity. What configuration is missing to enable on-premises access via Client VPN?","options":["A. VPN endpoint only","B. VPN endpoint + hybrid connectivity (DX/VPN) + authorization rules allowing client traffic to on-premises CIDR blocks","C. VPN endpoint with internet gateway","D. Client VPN automatically reaches on-premises"],"answer":1,"explain":"Client VPN requires explicit authorization rules for each route including on-premises networks. Hybrid connectivity must be in place. Route tables in VPC must point to on-premises via Transit Gateway/DX."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implementing AWS Network Firewall in centralized security VPC for all outbound traffic realizes that some legitimate traffic is being blocked. They need to add exceptions for specific destinations while maintaining DLP for sensitive data. What is the correct configuration?","options":["A. Disable rules for legitimate destinations","B. Create firewall rule groups with allow rules + DLP rules, ordered with allow-lists checked first for legitimate destinations, DLP rules for sensitive data","C. Move to security groups only","D. Network Firewall cannot handle DLP exceptions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Network Firewall rule groups can be ordered for precedence. Allow rules for legitimate destinations take priority. DLP rules with pattern matching catch sensitive data. Both security and business needs met."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company configures security group rules allowing instances to reference another security group for bidirectional microservice communication. This works for inbound from referenced group but outbound traffic is blocked. What is the most likely issue?","options":["A. The outbound security group rule is missing from the service SG","B. Both SGs need explicit outbound rules to the referenced SG OR both SGs need to allow 'self' references","C. Security group references only work for inbound traffic","D. NACLs are blocking the traffic"],"answer":0,"explain":"Security group references work bidirectionally IF CONFIGURED. Service SG needs explicit outbound rule allowing traffic to referenced SG. Inbound SG needs rule allowing traffic from service SG."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements Network Access Analyzer to verify connectivity between sensitive databases and public subnets. Analyzer shows reachable but traffic is still blocked. What does 'reachable' mean in this context and what is the issue?","options":["A. Reachable means traffic flows successfully","B. Reachable means no network-layer blocks exist (routes + NACLs + SGs allow); application-layer or service issues may still block actual traffic","C. Reachable means databases are online","D. Analyzer guarantees successful connectivity"],"answer":1,"explain":"Network Access Analyzer only verifies network-layer connectivity (routing, NACLs, SGs). Application-layer firewalls, TLS certificate issues, or service misconfigurations can still block traffic despite 'reachable' status."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements Web Application Firewall (WAF) with DDoS protection via AWS Shield Standard. Attack traffic reaches CloudFront but WAF rules don't trigger. What is the issue?","options":["A. Shield Standard doesn't protect against DDoS","B. WAF must be explicitly associated with CloudFront distribution + rules configured + Shield Advanced for Layer 3/4 DDoS protection","C. WAF automatically protects all CloudFront distributions","D. DDoS protection only works at the VPC level"],"answer":1,"explain":"WAF must be explicitly associated with CloudFront (or ALB/API Gateway). Shield Standard covers L3/4 but not application attacks. WAF rules must be configured. Shield Advanced adds comprehensive DDoS protection."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company uses VPC endpoint for S3 with gateway endpoint type to avoid NAT Gateway charges for S3 data transfer. However, CloudFormation templates still deploy with internet egress. What is the least invasive way to prevent S3 data leaving the VPC?","options":["A. Remove internet gateway","B. S3 bucket policy + endpoint policy: deny S3 access except via gateway endpoint + VPC route tables route S3 to gateway endpoint only","C. Enable S3 encryption","D. Use interface endpoint instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"Gateway endpoint policy + S3 bucket policy together deny access outside the endpoint. Routes direct traffic to endpoint. This prevents data egress without removing IGW or removing S3 access."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implementing NLB with TLS termination for internal east-west traffic between VPCs realizes that traffic is being inspected by AWS Network Firewall for DLP. The firewall sees encrypted traffic and cannot inspect. What configuration enables inspection of encrypted traffic?","options":["A. NLB TLS termination cannot be inspected","B. Deploy Network Firewall in transparent proxy mode with TLS-aware DLP rules OR terminate TLS before firewall and re-encrypt after","C. Disable TLS for inspection","D. Use WAF instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"Encrypted traffic is opaque to firewalls. Options: transparent proxy mode with TLS decryption inspection + re-encryption, or terminate TLS before DLP firewall."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company analyzing VPC Flow Logs realizes their application generates high data transfer costs but logs don't show the traffic. VPC Flow Logs show occasional REJECT entries for the IP range. What does a REJECT entry mean in flow logs?","options":["A. Packet was malformed","B. REJECT means traffic was dropped at network layer by NACLs or security groups (not reaching application)","C. REJECT means application refused the connection","D. REJECT indicates VPC issue"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC Flow Logs REJECT entries indicate network-layer drops (NACLs, security groups). ACCEPT entries reach the application. High costs with REJECT entries suggest misconfigured firewall rules dropping valid traffic."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company implements Transit Gateway Network Manager to monitor hybrid connectivity across 5 regions and 50 on-premises locations. They notice that some on-premises routers show 'no route found' but connectivity works. What does this indicate in Network Manager?","options":["A. Network Manager is inaccurate","B. Connectivity exists but routing is suboptimal or asymmetric; Network Manager shows topology issues even if basic connectivity works","C. The on-premises router is offline","D. Network Manager requires BGP for accuracy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Network Manager visualizes routing topology. 'No route' found indicates missing optimal routes even if basic connectivity exists via suboptimal paths. This reveals design issues like asymmetric routing."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company rolling out Application Load Balancer with health checks to multiple AZs notices that cross-AZ traffic costs are higher than expected. ALB distributes traffic across all healthy targets regardless of AZ. What load balancer feature minimizes cross-AZ traffic?","options":["A. Use NLB instead","B. Cross-Zone Load Balancing: disable to prefer same-AZ targets, or enable Availability Zone affinity at ALB","C. Cross-AZ traffic cannot be avoided","D. Place all targets in one AZ"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cross-Zone Load Balancing (enabled by default on ALB) distributes across AZs. Disabling it makes ALB prefer same-AZ targets, significantly reducing data transfer costs."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company implementing Reachability Analyzer to verify connectivity between RDS instance and application finds that Analyzer shows reachable but application still cannot connect. Route tables and security groups are verified correct. What is the most likely issue?","options":["A. Reachability Analyzer is broken","B. Reachability Analyzer verifies network-layer connectivity only; RDS encryption, database user permissions, or application code issues may still prevent connection","C. RDS must be in public subnet","D. Application must be in same AZ"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reachability Analyzer confirms network path (routes, SGs, NACLs) but not application-layer issues like RDS user credentials, TLS validation, or application connection string misconfiguration."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company enabling VPC Flow Logs for security investigation realizes that inter-VPC traffic via Transit Gateway is not appearing in VPC Flow Logs. Where should they look for this traffic?","options":["A. VPC Flow Logs for both source and destination VPCs should show it","B. Transit Gateway Flow Logs (separate service) capture inter-VPC traffic; VPC Flow Logs only show local VPC traffic","C. Inter-VPC traffic is never logged","D. Enable inter-VPC Flow Logs in Transit Gateway settings"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC Flow Logs capture traffic within a VPC. Transit Gateway Flow Logs (separate logs at TGW attachment level) capture inter-VPC and hybrid traffic. Both may be needed for complete visibility."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements VPC Lattice for service-to-service networking across VPCs and accounts. What advantage does Lattice provide over Transit Gateway for microservice connectivity?","options":["A. Lattice routes traffic more efficiently","B. Lattice provides service mesh capabilities: built-in service discovery, load balancing, and security policies at application layer without side-cars","C. Lattice replaces Transit Gateway","D. Lattice is only for container workloads"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC Lattice adds application-layer networking on top of Transit Gateway. Service discovery, load balancing, and policies at application level. Works for both containerized and traditional workloads."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with Global Accelerator distribution across 4 regions for ultra-low latency realizes that one region's endpoint is degraded but Global Accelerator still sends traffic. What configuration prevents sending traffic to degraded endpoints?","options":["A. Global Accelerator automatically handles degraded endpoints","B. Configure endpoint groups with health checks + traffic dials; failing health checks trigger automatic traffic dial adjustment or failover","C. Requires manual intervention","D. Global Accelerator cannot prevent degraded traffic"],"answer":1,"explain":"Global Accelerator endpoint groups have health checks (Bayesian averaging across multiple health checkers). Failed health checks can trigger traffic dials (weight adjustment) or complete failover."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing CloudFront for global content delivery with origin in private VPC realizes that origin access is slow and exposed to internet routing variability. What CloudFront feature provides optimized, private connectivity to origin?","options":["A. CloudFront Origin Shield only","B. Origin Access Identity (OAI) only","C. CloudFront Origin Access Control (OAC) + VPC origin with private connectivity via PrivateLink","D. CloudFront requires public origin"],"answer":2,"explain":"OAC + VPC origin with PrivateLink (origin group with private endpoints) provides encrypted, optimized, non-internet-routed connectivity from CloudFront to origin."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company deploying Lambda functions in VPC with CloudFront front-end realizes that Lambda functions cannot reach DynamoDB global tables in other regions through VPC. What is the issue and solution?","options":["A. Lambda in VPC has no internet access by default; add NAT Gateway for DynamoDB endpoint access","B. Lambda in VPC requires VPC endpoint for DynamoDB or internet egress via NAT Gateway","C. DynamoDB global tables require public endpoint","D. Lambda cannot access cross-region DynamoDB"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda in VPC has no default internet access. VPC endpoint for DynamoDB (uses private connectivity) OR NAT Gateway (for internet access) enables cross-region DynamoDB access."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A startup quickly grows from 1 VPC to 50 VPCs across 3 regions and realizes that managing 1,225 potential peering connections is unmanageable. What architectural refactoring immediately simplifies management?","options":["A. Implement AWS Transit Gateway per region with inter-region peering","B. VPC peering is the only option","C. Move all to single VPC","D. Use Global Accelerator instead"],"answer":0,"explain":"50 VPCs create (50 × 49) / 2 = 1,225 peering connections. Transit Gateway: 50 attachments + 1 inter-region connection = 51 total. Vastly simpler management and scaling."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company planning Direct Connect deployment realizes they need to support multiple virtual interfaces: public VIF for AWS APIs, private VIF for VPC traffic, and transit VIF for hybrid connectivity. What is the key difference of transit VIF?","options":["A. Transit VIF is faster than private VIF","B. Transit VIF enables connectivity through Transit Gateway, supporting on-premises to multiple VPCs","C. Transit VIF is public-only","D. Transit VIF is for CloudFront only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit VIF (available since April 2020) connects to Transit Gateway instead of a single VPC, enabling scalable connectivity from on-premises through Transit Gateway to all attached VPCs."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing 10 Gbps Direct Connect connection realizes that only 1 Gbps is actually being used despite multiple applications. What is the most likely issue and how can they debug?","options":["A. DX connection is underutilized","B. BGP configuration, routing weights, or application preference may be causing traffic to take suboptimal path; enable BGP multipath, check BGP weights, monitor with CloudWatch DX metrics","C. DX is working correctly","D. Application does not support high bandwidth"],"answer":1,"explain":"Even with 10 Gbps DX, traffic may prefer internet path or split suboptimally. BGP weights, cost metrics, and dynamic routing policies determine actual traffic distribution. Monitoring required."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company using Direct Connect with LAG across 4 physical connections realizes that one link is consistently dropping packets. What impact does this have on LAG and what should be configured?","options":["A. LAG continues working as other links compensate","B. Degraded link reduces overall throughput; for true redundancy configure additional LAG in different location with BGP failover, and monitor member link quality","C. LAG automatically removes degraded link","D. Switch to VPN"],"answer":1,"explain":"LAG spreads load across 4 links but degradation affects all. True redundancy requires geographically diverse backup LAG. Monitoring with CloudWatch alerts on packet loss is critical."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company deploying CloudFront with field-level encryption realizes that some encrypted fields cannot be decrypted by origin application due to key rotation. What feature enables key rotation without disrupting active traffic?","options":["A. CloudFront automatically rotates keys","B. Field-level encryption profiles with versioning + graceful key migration over time","C. Keys cannot be rotated while origin receives traffic","D. Disable field-level encryption for key rotation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Field-level encryption profiles support multiple key versions simultaneously. New requests use new key while old requests can still be decrypted with previous keys during rotation window."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing CloudFront with Lambda@Edge for header rewriting and geographic routing realizes that some URLs are not being rewritten. The Lambda function executes but headers remain unchanged. What is most likely wrong?","options":["A. Lambda@Edge syntax error","B. Lambda@Edge invoked on wrong event (viewer-request vs origin-request); ensure Lambda returns request/response object with modified headers","C. Headers cannot be modified by Lambda@Edge","D. Requires origin configuration change"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda@Edge on viewer-request can modify headers before sending to origin. Ensure Lambda returns the modified request object. viewer-response modifies origin-returned headers. Improper event selection causes silent failures."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company using CloudFront origin groups for failover realizes that one origin is responding with 500 errors but CloudFront still sends traffic to it. What is the issue?","options":["A. Origin groups require manual health check configuration","B. CloudFront automatically fails over on network errors but not application errors (5xx); configure cache behavior error codes to trigger failover","C. Origin groups don't support failover","D. Must use Global Accelerator instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront origin groups failover on connection errors. Application errors (5xx, 4xx) don't trigger failover by default. Configure cache behaviors to failover on specific HTTP error codes."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures Site-to-Site VPN with two tunnels for HA. During failover testing, traffic is intermittently lost even though BGP shows both tunnels up. What BGP configuration prevents split-brain?","options":["A. BGP automatically handles dual tunnels","B. Configure BGP timers (keepalive/hold) identically + same BGP ASN on both tunnels + higher priority on primary tunnel via local preference","C. Tunnels must use different ASNs","D. VPN failover cannot be graceful"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dual VPN tunnels with identical BGP timers ensure clean transition. Primary tunnel configured with higher local preference; backup takes over only on primary failure."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implementing AWS Client VPN for remote workers realizes that some DNS queries from clients are timing out even though the VPN tunnel is up. Where are DNS queries being resolved and what is the issue?","options":["A. Client VPN automatically provides DNS","B. Client VPN does not provide DNS resolution; clients use their default DNS (usually ISP). Configure Client VPN endpoint settings to push Route 53 Resolver IPs + push search domains","C. All DNS must be on-premises","D. DNS tunneling through VPN"],"answer":1,"explain":"Client VPN is layer 3 only. DNS resolution depends on client OS DNS settings. VPN endpoint DNS settings can push Route 53 Resolver or on-premises DNS to clients via DHCP options."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company with dual VPN connections to AWS observes asymmetric latency (high latency outbound, low latency inbound) and blames the VPN provider. BGP is configured. What is the actual issue?","options":["A. VPN provider has poor quality","B. Asymmetric routing: return traffic taking different path; verify BGP routes are symmetric or use GRE tunnels with BGP to enforce consistent paths","C. VPN MTU too small","D. AWS-side issue"],"answer":1,"explain":"Without proper BGP configuration or policy, traffic might leave via VPN1 but return via VPN2, which may have different latency characteristics. BGP configuration must enforce symmetric paths."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements AWS Shield Standard for DDoS protection but still gets hit with L3/L4 DDoS causing connectivity issues. Standard protection failed. What is the correct protection mix?","options":["A. Shield Standard covers all DDoS attacks","B. Shield Standard provides basic L3/L4 but may not prevent largest attacks; Shield Advanced provides proactive monitoring + comprehensive protection + DDoS cost protection","C. DDoS cannot be prevented","D. WAF alone covers DDoS"],"answer":1,"explain":"Shield Standard covers common DDoS (SYN floods, UDP reflection). Shield Advanced adds proactive monitoring via DDoS threat intelligence, larger scale protection, and automatic mitigation for largest attacks."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements Network Firewall with stateful rules but realizes that TCP connections are being dropped randomly even though rules should allow them. What must be configured for stateful connection handling?","options":["A. Rules only","B. Stateful rules + connection timeout settings + TCP flags validation (must see SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK sequence); verify connection tracking state is enabled","C. Firewall cannot handle stateful connections","D. Disable stateful and use UDP instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"Network Firewall stateful engine tracks TCP connection state. Timeout settings must match application patterns. Improper TCP flags or sequence issues cause random drops."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company uses VPC endpoint for DynamoDB with a restrictive policy that blocks all access except read operations. However, legitimate write operations are failing with AccessDenied. What is missing?","options":["A. Endpoint policy is blocking writes","B. Both VPC endpoint policy AND DynamoDB table/GSI policy must permit writes; endpoint policy alone cannot restrict table-level operations completely if table policy allows","C. DynamoDB endpoints do not support writes","D. Use interface endpoint instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC endpoint policy controls access at endpoint level. DynamoDB table policy controls access at table level. Both must permit the action. Restrictive endpoint policy on writes blocks all write operations."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company analyzes VPC Flow Logs and sees traffic marked as ACCEPTED but with very high BYTES values concentrated in specific time windows. Investigation reveals data exfiltration via DNS tunneling. Why wasn't this caught?","options":["A. VPC Flow Logs are incomplete","B. VPC Flow Logs only show network-layer info (flows, bytes, source/dest); application-layer detection (DNS tunneling patterns) requires separate DLP tools like Network Firewall with DNS inspection","C. DNS cannot be monitored","D. Need different VPC Flow Logs configuration"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC Flow Logs show the flow exists and bytes transferred but not the payload. DNS inspection via Network Firewall rules can detect tunneling patterns (abnormal query sizes/rates)."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company deploying multi-region Transit Gateway realizes that inter-region traffic is showing high latency spikes. Transit Gateway Flow Logs show traffic is reaching the peer region. What is the issue?","options":["A. Transit Gateway inter-region peering is slow","B. High latency likely due to destination region routing, destination VPC route table configuration, or destination resource placement; use Reachability Analyzer + latency metrics to diagnose","C. Should use VPC peering instead","D. Multi-region is inherently slow"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit Gateway inter-region peering is transparent. Latency spikes indicate destination-side issues. Reachability Analyzer confirms path. CloudWatch metrics show endpoint quality. Destination resource placement affects latency."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company implements VPC Flow Logs for security monitoring but the log volume is overwhelming (100GB/day) making analysis difficult. What is the most effective solution?","options":["A. Disable VPC Flow Logs","B. Enable flow logs at higher granularity + use Athena queries + CloudWatch Insights for pattern detection + set retention to 24-48 hours for hot analysis","C. Store all logs indefinitely","D. Disable logging on internal traffic"],"answer":1,"explain":"High volume requires granular logging (interface level vs all traffic) + analysis tools (Athena for ad-hoc queries, CloudWatch Insights for anomalies) + retention policies matching security SLA."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing AWS Organizations with 50 accounts across 5 regions realizes that Transit Gateway attachment scaling is becoming complex. What centralized networking service can simplify?","options":["A. Continue with Transit Gateway only","B. AWS Cloud WAN for centralized policy management of Transit Gateways across organization + network monitoring + policy-based routing","C. Move to VPC peering","D. Separate Transit Gateways per region indefinitely"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cloud WAN provides organization-level networking management. Simplified policy creation, enforcement across all regions/accounts, unified monitoring. Especially valuable for large organizations."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company deploying machine learning workloads requires extremely high bandwidth (100+ Gbps) between GPU clusters in different AZs. VPC peering/Transit Gateway latency is acceptable but bandwidth is insufficient. What is the solution?","options":["A. Use standard VPC networking with optimization","B. VPC Lattice (does not help bandwidth) + place GPU clusters in single AZ is suboptimal; only solution is AWS HPC Cluster Placement Group + Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) for high-bandwidth inter-node communication","C. Requires custom Direct Connect","D. Cannot achieve 100+ Gbps"],"answer":1,"explain":"HPC Cluster Placement Groups + Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) provide single-digit microsecond latency + 100+ Gbps bandwidth for tightly-coupled HPC/ML workloads within single AZ."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with disaster recovery requirement (RPO 1 hour, RTO 15 minutes) implements active-passive failover with Route 53 health checks. During regional failure, failover completes in 45 seconds but business impact is still significant. What optimization reduces RTO?","options":["A. Faster health checks only","B. Combine DNS failover (15 seconds per max TTL) with application-level health checks + warm standby instance + pre-warmed data caches; pre-warmed warm standby provides immediate availability","C. RPO/RTO cannot be improved","D. Requires instant full active-active (expensive)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Passive failover has inherent delays: health check detection + DNS propagation (TTL). Warm standby (partially running standby) + data pre-warming + application-level health checks reduce practical RTO."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures asymmetric routing between on-premises and AWS intentionally (outbound via DX, return via VPN for cost optimization). Certain protocols fail with this asymmetry. What protocol is most affected?","options":["A. TCP always works","B. UDP and stateful protocols break with asymmetric routing (ICMP, many VPN protocols detect source/dest mismatch). Only TCP with proper sequence tracking survives asymmetry","C. All protocols work with asymmetry","D. Firewall prevents asymmetry"],"answer":1,"explain":"Asymmetric routing breaks stateful protocols that validate source/dest consistency. ICMP, IPSec ESP, and UDP-based VPNs fail. TCP usually survives but introduces performance issues."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements redundant NAT Gateways in each subnet for high availability. During testing, one NAT Gateway fails and instances lose outbound connectivity despite healthy NAT Gateway in same AZ. What is the issue?","options":["A. One NAT Gateway per AZ failed correctly","B. Route table points to first NAT Gateway only; must modify route table or distribute with separate route tables per NAT Gateway / use load balancing for NAT","C. NAT Gateways cannot be redundant","D. Requires second AZ immediately"],"answer":1,"explain":"NAT Gateway redundancy requires both failover mechanism AND proper routing. Single route table entry points to one NAT. To use multiple NAT Gateways: separate route tables per AZ or load balance NAT traffic."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implementing Network Firewall for egress filtering realizes that traffic to AWS service endpoints (S3, DynamoDB) is being blocked. What must be configured to allow AWS service access while blocking other egress?","options":["A. Whitelist all AWS service IPs","B. Create firewall rules allowing VPC endpoint CIDR blocks + allow to AWS service prefix lists (maintained by AWS) + deny all else","C. Cannot block egress to AWS services","D. Use security groups instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS service endpoints require explicit allow rules. AWS prefix lists (published per region) specify IP ranges. Firewall rules must reference these + VPC endpoint security groups."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company using security groups for segmentation realizes that circular dependencies are created: SG-A allows traffic from SG-B, SG-B allows from SG-C, SG-C allows from SG-A. This creates an unintended trust relationship. What is the architectural issue and solution?","options":["A. Security groups handle this fine","B. Circular SG dependencies create unintended trust paths. Solution: minimize SG cross-references + use NACLs for explicit deny-all rules on sensitive subnets","C. Requires separate VPC","D. Cannot be solved with SGs"],"answer":1,"explain":"Security groups are stateful allows. Circular references create implicit trust paths. NACLs add explicit deny layers. Best practice: minimize SG cross-references, use NACLs for deny-all baseline."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing Route 53 geoproximity routing with bias realizes that traffic is always routed to nearest geographic region, causing uneven load distribution. What does bias parameter control?","options":["A. Bias expands/contracts geographic radius for weighted distribution","B. Bias (signed 1-99 or -1 to -99) adjusts preferred region radius. Positive bias expands, negative contracts. Enables load distribution away from always-nearest geography","C. Bias is random distribution","D. Bias has no effect"],"answer":1,"explain":"Bias parameter shifts traffic from pure geographic proximity. Positive bias encourages traffic to preferred region. Negative bias directs away. Enables load balancing with geographic awareness."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company deploying multi-protocol DNS (Route 53 + private zone + Resolver) for compliance realizes that recursive DNS queries from on-premises for AWS resources are slow. What configuration reduces latency?","options":["A. Public hosted zones only","B. Route 53 Resolver inbound endpoint in VPC + conditional forwarding from on-premises resolvers to inbound endpoint (avoids internet routing) + proper TTL caching","C. No solution","D. Move DNS to on-premises"],"answer":1,"explain":"On-premises DNS recursively queries Route 53 via internet. Inbound Resolver endpoint provides direct, private connectivity for DNS queries. Conditional forwarding eliminates internet latency."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with strict data sovereignty requirements (no internet egress) uses gateway endpoints for S3/DynamoDB. They realize other AWS services require interface endpoints. What is the architectural difference and cost implication?","options":["A. Both endpoints have same cost","B. Gateway endpoints are free (no hourly charge); interface endpoints charge hourly + per-GB processed. Multiple interface endpoints increase cost significantly","C. Interface endpoints are always cheaper","D. Cannot use both together"],"answer":1,"explain":"Gateway endpoints (S3, DynamoDB) are free. Interface endpoints charge $0.01/hour + $0.01/GB. Deploying interface endpoints per service per AZ creates cost. Design endpoint architecture carefully."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company creates VPC endpoint service for multiple customer accounts but realizes that consumer account IPs are not visible in producer logs. Why, and what must be configured for IP visibility?","options":["A. Consumer IPs are always hidden","B. PrivateLink hides consumer IPs by default for privacy; enable 'Preserve client IP' in producer service to see real consumer IPs; consumer SG must allow producer service IPs","C. Not possible with PrivateLink","D. Requires application-layer logging"],"answer":1,"explain":"PrivateLink source IP masquerading is default for privacy. Producer service can enable client IP preservation in Advanced options. Network interfaces must have source IP tracking."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company deploying NLB with UDP for DNS/gaming realizes that some packets are lost during traffic spikes. NLB is showing packet drops. What must be configured for UDP reliability?","options":["A. NLB handles UDP perfectly","B. NLB UDP can drop packets under load. Solution: configure connection flow limits + healthy target pool size + monitor target CPU/network + scale targets","C. UDP is unreliable","D. Must use TCP instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"NLB UDP works well but under extreme load can drop packets. Connection flow limits protect targets. Proper target scaling and monitoring prevent overload-related loss."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements ALB with host-based routing for multi-tenant SaaS. Each customer gets subdomain (customer.example.com) routed to separate target group. One customer experiences higher latency than others. What causes uneven performance?","options":["A. ALB is broken","B. ALB distributes connections evenly but target quality varies. Customer's target group may have fewer/weaker instances, degraded targets, or targets in same AZ causing imbalance","C. Subdomains are handled equally","D. Requires separate ALB"],"answer":1,"explain":"ALB routing is fast/consistent. Performance differences come from target pool quality. Some target groups may have underpowered instances, failed health checks, or suboptimal AZ distribution."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company implements CloudWatch metrics for NLB but the 'ActiveConnectionCount' metric shows very high values while actual connection rate is low. What does this metric actually measure and why is it high?","options":["A. It is broken","B. ActiveConnectionCount is total concurrent connections (not just new connections). High value if connections are long-lived (WebSockets, keep-alive, VPN) which is normal","C. New connections only","D. Maximum capacity"],"answer":1,"explain":"ActiveConnectionCount is concurrent open connections. WebSocket, keep-alive, VPN connections remain open indefinitely. High count is normal for these protocols; not an error."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company monitoring Transit Gateway with CloudWatch observes 'BytesDropped' metric spiking at specific times daily. This correlates with backups. What is likely happening and what should be checked?","options":["A. Bytes are lost","B. BytesDropped may indicate CIDR conflicts causing packets to be dropped during routing lookup (check for overlapping CIDR blocks in attached VPCs)","C. Transit Gateway is broken","D. Backups are misconfigured"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit Gateway BytesDropped indicates routing failures or CIDR conflicts. Backup traffic spike may trigger drops if multiple VPCs use overlapping CIDRs discovered during high-volume periods."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures BGP on Direct Connect with AS path prepending for traffic engineering (primary path with longer AS path, backup with shorter). Traffic still prefers shorter path. What is wrong?","options":["A. BGP is misconfigured","B. BGP AS path determines preference but local preference overrides it. Check BGP local preference configuration; ensure primary has higher local preference than backup","C. BGP cannot do traffic engineering","D. Direct Connect ignores BGP"],"answer":1,"explain":"BGP decision process: local preference > AS path length. AS path prepending alone doesn't work if other BGP attributes favor backup. Set higher local preference on primary path."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implementing multi-path BGP over two Direct Connect connections realizes that some traffic goes to DX1, rest to DX2, but not perfectly balanced. How do you enable true ECMP (equal-cost multi-path)?","options":["A. BGP automatically does load balancing","B. BGP ECMP requires identical cost metrics: MED (multi-exit discriminator), local preference, and AS path must match. Configure identical MED on both paths","C. Cannot be done with BGP","D. Use static routing instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"BGP only load-balances when routes are truly equal-cost. Different MED, local preference, or AS path length causes imbalanced distribution. Identical metrics required for 50/50 split."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements route aggregation (summarization) on Direct Connect to reduce BGP advertisement volume. Customer Gateway aggregates 100 /24 networks into single /16 advertisement. What problem occurs?","options":["A. Aggregation works perfectly","B. Aggregation works but may create routing blackholes for non-existent subnets within aggregate + increases convergence time on changes. Use no-export community to limit propagation","C. AWS does not support aggregation","D. Cannot reduce advertisements"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route aggregation reduces routing overhead but risks. Blackholes for gaps in aggregated range. Proper aggregate configuration + using communities to limit propagation is essential."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company designs VPC with /18 CIDR (16,384 addresses) for 10,000 instances across 4 AZs and 3 tiers. They allocate /21 per tier per AZ. After 6 months, database tier is exhausted. How should they redesign?","options":["A. Migrate to new VPC","B. Add secondary CIDR block to VPC OR reallocate existing ranges with 2x capacity per tier + migrate instances","C. Cannot expand","D. Request larger CIDR from AWS"],"answer":1,"explain":"Secondary CIDR blocks allow expansion without migration. Alternatively, redesign allocation based on actual growth (database > application) and pre-plan growth with secondary blocks reserved."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with multiple VPCs in same region realizes that routing is complex due to overlapping CIDR blocks (unintended). They must fix without full redesign. What is the least disruptive solution?","options":["A. Migrate all to new VPCs","B. Use Transit Gateway with route tables filtering overlapping traffic + NAT Instances to translate overlaps + gradual VPC isolation migration","C. Cannot fix overlaps","D. Use load balancers to route around"],"answer":1,"explain":"Overlapping CIDRs are dangerous but can be managed temporarily. Transit Gateway route tables can selectively route. NAT Instances can translate addresses. Full fix requires redesign with non-overlapping CIDRs."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements Network Firewall with rules for intrusion prevention (IPS). They configure signature-based rule groups for known malware detection. Traffic is blocked but a new variant bypasses rules. What additional protection is needed?","options":["A. Signature rules only","B. Signature-based IPS + behavioral/anomaly detection + external threat intelligence integration for zero-day protection","C. Cannot block zero-day","D. WAF only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Signature rules detect known threats. Behavioral analysis and threat intelligence feeds detect anomalies and zero-days. Combined approach provides comprehensive protection."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company configures Network Firewall with stateful rules allowing tcp port 443 inbound. However, responses to outbound HTTPS connections are sometimes blocked. What is the issue?","options":["A. Rule is correct","B. Stateful rules match bidirectional traffic. Outbound HTTPS (sport high, dport 443) returns with sport 443, dport high. Inbound rule (sport any, dport 443) doesn't match return traffic. Need explicit outbound return rule","C. HTTPS cannot be stateful","D. Firewall is broken"],"answer":1,"explain":"Firewall rules must match both directions. Inbound rule for port 443 doesn't automatically permit return traffic from outbound HTTPS. Explicit return rules or stateful handling required."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company with on-premises VPN to AWS realizes that traffic spikes cause intermittent packet loss. VPN tunnel shows 100% utilization. What configuration prevents this?","options":["A. Increase VPN encryption strength","B. VPN bandwidth is limited. Solutions: add second VPN + use Direct Connect for primary + burst capacity management via traffic queuing/shaping","C. VPN cannot handle spikes","D. Disable encryption for speed"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPN over internet has bandwidth limits. Under-provisioned bandwidth causes drops. Multiple VPNs or Direct Connect provides higher sustained capacity. Traffic shaping prevents overrun."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements Site-to-Site VPN with dynamic routing. During failover from primary to backup VPN, traffic is interrupted for 30 seconds. What minimizes failover time?","options":["A. Faster BGP timers only","B. BGP timers (keepalive 3s, hold 9s) + fast VPN tunnel status detection (HelloInterval 3s) + faster route propagation configuration","C. Cannot be optimized","D. Switch to static routing"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPN failover involves tunnel detection + BGP convergence. Aggressive timers (shorter hold times, faster hello) reduce convergence from 30s to <10s. Balance with stability (not too aggressive)."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company using CloudFront for content delivery notices that some end users get stale content despite Cache-Control headers being correct. What is the likely issue and solution?","options":["A. CloudFront is broken","B. CloudFront respects Cache-Control but different cache behaviors may have different TTLs. Some edge locations may have older objects. Use cache invalidation + versioned URLs for immediate updates","C. Cannot guarantee fresh content","D. Disable caching"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront distributed cache means objects may be stale at some edges. Cache invalidation explicitly purges. Versioned URLs (e.g., /file-v123.js) bypass caching for new versions."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing CloudFront with multiple origin groups for failover realizes that failover happens too slowly when primary origin becomes unhealthy. How can they detect failures faster?","options":["A. CloudFront automatically detects","B. Configure lower cache TTLs for error responses + custom cache behaviors with specific error codes + additional origin health checks via Route 53","C. Cannot be faster","D. Disable caching for speed"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront origin health depends on response codes and cache TTL. Lower error response TTLs (e.g., 10s for 5xx errors) enable faster detection. External health checks improve reliability."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements Global Accelerator for gaming platform with low-latency requirements. Some users experience high packet loss despite low latency. What is the likely issue?","options":["A. Global Accelerator is broken","B. Global Accelerator provides low latency but packet loss depends on endpoint quality + target health. High packet loss suggests unhealthy targets. Check endpoint health checks + scale targets","C. Packet loss cannot be fixed","D. Use CloudFront instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"Global Accelerator optimizes latency via anycast routing but reliability depends on backend endpoints. Failing health checks or overloaded targets cause loss. Proper target scaling essential."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company using Global Accelerator with traffic dials to shift traffic (90% region A, 10% region B) realizes that some requests still go to region B despite low traffic dial weight. Why does traffic not strictly follow dial distribution?","options":["A. Traffic dials are exact","B. Traffic dials are probabilistic across many clients over time. Individual request routing varies but aggregate approach specified weight. Some requests may go to non-primary due to connection reuse","C. Traffic dials don't work","D. Requires exact routing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Global Accelerator traffic dials use probabilistic distribution over time, not strict per-connection routing. Some requests to low-weight region are expected. Monitor aggregate distribution."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements IPv6 in VPC with Egress-Only Internet Gateway for IPv6 outbound. They launch dual-stack instances (IPv4 + IPv6). Some clients cannot reach IPv6 addresses. What is missing?","options":["A. EIGW only","B. Need IPv6 route table entries + EIGW + ensure target has public IPv6 address OR Elastic IPv6 + security group rules for IPv6 traffic","C. IPv6 needs internet gateway","D. Clients do not support IPv6"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dual-stack requires: VPC + subnet IPv6 CIDR, instance IPv6 address, route table entries (route ::/0 to EIGW), security groups permitting IPv6. Missing any breaks reachability."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company expanding to IPv6 realizes that some legacy on-premises systems cannot resolve IPv6 addresses. They need to maintain IPv4-only on-premises while supporting IPv6 in AWS. What must be configured?","options":["A. IPv6 only in AWS","B. Dual-stack in AWS + Route 53 Resolver with conditional forwarding handling IPv4-only queries from on-premises + NAT64 translation for on-prem IPv4 clients reaching IPv6-only resources","C. Cannot mix IPv4 and IPv6","D. Force IPv6 on-premises"],"answer":1,"explain":"NAT64 translates IPv6 addresses to IPv4 for IPv4-only clients. Resolver forwarding rules handle address family differences. Hybrid IPv4/IPv6 possible with proper translation."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company uses VPC peering between 5 VPCs for inter-application communication. They realize that all traffic must be explicitly routed in each VPC's route table, causing management overhead. What alternative has simpler routing?","options":["A. VPC peering is the only option","B. VPC peering is non-transitive; Transit Gateway provides single hop for all VPCs + automatic route propagation + transitive routing","C. Cannot simplify routing","D. Merge all VPCs"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC peering requires individual route table entries per peer pair. Transit Gateway hub-and-spoke requires fewer routes + automatic propagation + transitive routing for multi-hop communication."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with established VPC peering between production and development VPCs realizes they need to revoke developer access without breaking applications. The route must remain but traffic must be blocked. What is the solution?","options":["A. Delete the peering connection","B. Keep peering + route but restrict via NACL + security groups on development targets + consider removing route for complete block","C. Cannot prevent traffic with peering","D. Separate networks"],"answer":1,"explain":"Peering enables reachability but NACLs and SGs enforce actual access. Remove application-level access via SG/NACL without deleting peering. Route can stay disabled for efficiency."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company implements VPC Flow Logs with Athena for querying. They want to find all sources that accessed a specific database security group. What Athena query pattern should they use?","options":["A. Simple select * query","B. Filter on dstport (database port) AND dstip (database SG CIDR) + group by srcip + filter for accepts only. Complex because SG membership requires context lookup","C. Cannot query SG membership","D. Use CloudWatch Logs only"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC Flow Logs contain IPs/ports but not security group names. Querying requires: dstport/dstip matching + cross-reference with SG rules. Best practice: enriched logs with SG context."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company monitoring TransitGateway Flow Logs detects high volume of flow-reject-entries with invalid source IP. When they check the source subnet's route table, no route exists for that destination. What is happening?","options":["A. Source route is correct","B. Flow-reject indicates dropped traffic. No matching route in source VPC route table for destination = traffic dropped at source TGW attachment before forwarding","C. TGW is broken","D. Source is spoofing"],"answer":1,"explain":"TGW route tables control attachment behavior. Missing route = packet dropped at TGW (flow-reject). Check TGW route table entries + attachment propagation + spoke route tables."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company tunnels traffic between on-premises and AWS via GRE (Generic Routing Encapsulation) with BGP. They realize GRE tunnel overhead reduces available bandwidth by 20%. What optimization reduces overhead?","options":["A. GRE overhead is fixed","B. GRE adds 24 bytes per packet (fixed). IPSec over GRE adds more overhead. Solutions: optimize packet size (larger payloads reduce overhead %), use BGP route aggregation","C. Cannot reduce overhead","D. Disable GRE"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tunnel overhead is per-packet. Larger packets (jumbo frames) reduce percentage overhead. Route aggregation reduces BGP load. Proper MTU configuration (1500 - overhead = payload MTU) optimizes."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements IPSec tunnel with AES-256 encryption but measures throughput and detects 30% performance overhead vs. non-encrypted tunnel. Is this expected and how to optimize?","options":["A. IPSec overhead is always 30%","B. Encryption overhead depends on CPU, algorithms, hardware acceleration. AES-256 stronger but slower than AES-128. Enable hardware acceleration (AES-NI) + tune encryption algorithm per security requirements","C. Cannot optimize","D. Disable encryption"],"answer":1,"explain":"IPSec CPU overhead varies. Modern CPUs with AES-NI hardware acceleration can encrypt at line rate. Choosing AES-128 over AES-256 trades security for speed. Profile actual throughput."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements active-active multi-region with Route 53 geoproximity routing. They realize that during regional failure, some users are still routed to failed region (DNS cache). What solution reduces user impact?","options":["A. Lower TTL only","B. Combine DNS failover (geoproximity + health checks) with TTL 60-120s + application-level circuit breaker + health check from multiple locations for faster convergence","C. Cannot improve user experience during failure","D. Instant failover only"],"answer":1,"explain":"TTL determines cache lifetime. Lower TTL (60s) enables faster failover than default 300s. Health checks from multiple regions detect failures faster. Circuit breakers stop retries to failed endpoints."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with RTO of 5 minutes implements warm standby in secondary region. They realize actual failover takes 15 minutes due to data synchronization lag. How to meet RTO?","options":["A. RTO target is unrealistic","B. Reduce RTO by: active-active with real-time replication (DynamoDB global tables), pre-warmed standby databases (warm standby = cold + pre-cache data), DNS failover + health checks","C. Cannot improve","D. Requires instant full active-active"],"answer":1,"explain":"5-minute RTO requires pre-warmed standby. Synchronous replication to standby databases + pre-cached data + DNS health checks = sub-5m failover. Balances cost vs. RTO."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements NAT Instance for highly available outbound traffic. They configure NAT Instance in multiple subnets across AZs. During NAT Instance failover in one AZ, traffic from that AZ intermittently fails. Why?","options":["A. NAT Instance is broken","B. Route table points to primary NAT in AZ-A. When NAT fails, traffic to unchanged route drops. Need separate route tables per AZ pointing to local NAT OR automated failover via ASG/health checks","C. NAT Instances cannot be HA","D. Requires multiple route tables"],"answer":1,"explain":"NAT Instance HA requires: routing to local NAT per AZ (separate route tables) OR automated failover replacing failed NAT. Single NAT Instance becomes bottleneck/SPOF."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures VPC endpoint for EC2 API and realizes that calls to ec2:DescribeInstances timeout despite endpoint being reachable. What might be wrong?","options":["A. Endpoint is broken","B. Endpoint reached but policy restricts action. VPC endpoint policies control what actions are allowed. Check: endpoint policy + IAM role policy + resource policy + network ACLs","C. Cannot call EC2 via endpoint","D. Requires special configuration"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC endpoints enforce authorization at multiple layers. Connectivity doesn't equal authorization. Endpoint policy must allow action + IAM role must permit it + NACLs must allow."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements NACL with deny rule for high-risk ports (23, 21, 22 telnet/ftp/ssh ingress) but realizes SSH still works into instances. Why?","options":["A. NACL deny is broken","B. NACLs are stateless. Deny inbound port 22 blocks incoming SSH but response traffic is outbound (port 22 source = allowed outbound by default). Security groups block unsolicited inbound","C. NACL cannot block SSH","D. NACL ignores deny"],"answer":1,"explain":"NACL inbound deny stops SSH but ephemeral return traffic (dport 22 from remote source) is outbound = different rule. Security groups are stateful + better for host-level control."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements Route 53 health checks for primary and secondary endpoints. Both health checks pass but some clients report connection failures. What could be wrong?","options":["A. Health checks are accurate","B. Health checks measure endpoint accessibility but not application functionality. DNS returns primary IP despite application errors. Solution: custom health checks with application-aware probing","C. Cannot improve health checks","D. Requires more health checkers"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 health checks verify connectivity but not application state. Health endpoint at /health returning 200 doesn't mean application functions. Custom health checks + application monitoring needed."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements Route 53 traffic policy for complex routing but policy evaluation seems slow, adding latency. How to optimize Route 53 performance?","options":["A. Route 53 is slow inherently","B. Route 53 response latency is typically <100ms. Slow responses indicate: complex policy logic (>100 rules) + excessive evaluations. Optimize by: simplifying policies, using CloudFront for DNS caching, reducing health check frequency","C. Cannot optimize","D. Disable traffic policies"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 is fast but complex traffic policies can add latency. CloudFront caches DNS responses. Reducing health check frequency from 10s to 30s decreases overhead. Simplify policy rules."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements ELB with sticky sessions for application affinity. During autoscaling event when old instances terminate, sticky sessions cause traffic to disconnect. How to handle graceful shutdown?","options":["A. Sticky sessions are always problematic","B. Configure connection draining (deregistration delay) on ELB + session expiration on application + graceful shutdown signal to drain existing connections before terminating","C. Cannot be graceful","D. Disable sticky sessions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Connection draining allows in-flight requests to complete before instance removal. Application graceful shutdown + deregistration delay coordinate to prevent dropped connections."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements AWS WAF rules blocking SQL injection patterns. Legitimate searches containing SQL keywords (SELECT, OR) are being blocked. How to whitelist legitimate traffic?","options":["A. WAF rules cannot be bypassed","B. Configure WAF with rate-based rules + allow lists for known good sources + specific path/header exceptions + custom rule groups with safe SQL pattern validation instead of keyword matching","C. Cannot fix false positives","D. Disable WAF for these users"],"answer":1,"explain":"Keyword-based rules generate false positives. Better approach: contextual analysis (WHERE clause syntax validation) + allow lists + custom rule groups + exception rules per application."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with on-premises HPC cluster connects to AWS for burst computing. They implement 10 Gbps Direct Connect but realize bandwidth utilization is only 40%. What causes underutilization?","options":["A. DX speed is set correctly","B. Underutilization due to: latency causing low TCP window size / single application thread / BGP route preference issues / asymmetric routing. Profile: check TCP throughput / BGP routes / network path","C. Cannot be improved","D. Network is misconfigured"],"answer":1,"explain":"DX underutilization typically comes from application-layer issues (single thread) or TCP tuning (window size, buffer). Profile actual throughput per connection to diagnose."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"An organization implementing multi-account architecture with 100+ AWS accounts realizes that managing Transit Gateway attachments per account is cumbersome. What service streamlines this?","options":["A. Continue manual management","B. AWS Cloud WAN provides automated Transit Gateway management across organization + centralized policy + simplified onboarding","C. Requires separate TGW per account","D. Use VPC peering instead"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cloud WAN automates TGW lifecycle management. Policies apply organization-wide. New accounts auto-connect per policy. Eliminates manual attachment management."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements Network Firewall across three AZs with redundant appliances. One AZ appliance fails and causes traffic blackhole instead of failing over. What is the configuration issue?","options":["A. Network Firewall automatically fails over","B. Network Firewall deployment requires: health checks on appliances + route updates on failure. Failing appliance must trigger route table update to bypass it via secondary appliance","C. Cannot be done","D. Requires manual intervention"],"answer":1,"explain":"Firewall appliance failure creates blackhole unless routes automatically update. Health check + Lambda/EventBridge rule updates routing on failure. Essential for HA."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company designs network for manufacturing IoT devices that generate 1 TB/day data upload to AWS. Low latency is critical (< 100ms). Cost is secondary. What connectivity is optimal?","options":["A. Site-to-Site VPN","B. Direct Connect to nearest AWS region with colocation + Local Zone endpoint for ultra-local connectivity","C. Internet gateway","D. CloudFront only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Direct Connect colocation provides guaranteed low latency + high throughput for bulk data. AWS Local Zones extend to customer facilities for sub-10ms latency when available."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures Elastic Load Balancer with cross-zone load balancing disabled to minimize inter-AZ costs. This works correctly for normal traffic but during AZ failure, remaining capacity is insufficient. What is the trade-off?","options":["A. Disable cross-zone always","B. Cross-zone disabled = lower data transfer costs but capacity concentrated per AZ. AZ failure = overload. Enable during outages or accept reduced capacity","C. No trade-off","D. Must enable always"],"answer":1,"explain":"Disabling cross-zone saves $0.006/GB but concentrates load. AZ failure with disabled cross-zone = dropped traffic. HA requires either: enable cross-zone OR over-provision per AZ."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements AWS Web Application Firewall on ALB with rules denying traffic to /admin* paths. However, encoded URIs like /admin%2F* bypass the rule. How to fix?","options":["A. WAF rules don't handle encoding","B. WAF XSS/SQL injection rules include decoding but path rules may not. Enable URI decoding in WAF + add rules for encoded patterns","C. Cannot prevent encoded attacks","D. Disable WAF for admin"],"answer":1,"explain":"WAF text transformations (decode URI, lowercase) must be configured per rule. Path rules without decoding miss encoded attacks. Enable transformation + test encoded variants."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company monitors VPC Flow Logs and detects regular ACCEPT entries for port 443 between two instances with exceptionally high byte count per flow (10GB+). This is unusual. What should they investigate?","options":["A. Normal large transfers","B. Anomalously large flows may indicate: data exfiltration / misconfigured replication / application bug. Correlate with CloudWatch Logs / application metrics / DLP tools","C. VPC Flow Logs are accurate","D. Cannot investigate further"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC Flow Logs show flows exist with byte counts but not content. Correlation with other logs (CloudWatch, CloudTrail, DLP) reveals intent. Large data flows warrant investigation."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with disaster recovery requirement implements continuous replication to secondary region. They realize replication traffic itself is a bottleneck consuming 80% of network capacity. How to optimize?","options":["A. Replication cannot be optimized","B. Optimize by: incremental replication (only changes) + compression + Direct Connect dedicated connection for replication + off-peak replication scheduling + reduced frequency (RPO trade-off)","C. Increase primary bandwidth","D. Disable replication during peak"],"answer":1,"explain":"Continuous full replication is expensive. Incremental + compression reduce traffic significantly. Dedicated DX connection separates replication from application traffic. RPO/bandwidth trade-off."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements NAT Gateway for instance outbound traffic. During sustained high-throughput file transfer, connections start failing with connection timeout. What is the limit being hit?","options":["A. Network bandwidth only","B. NAT Gateway: 55,000 concurrent connections per Elastic IP. Exceeding this limit = connection refused. Solutions: add additional NAT Gateway / add Elastic IPs to existing NAT","C. Cannot exceed","D. Instances are overloaded"],"answer":1,"explain":"NAT Gateway connection limit is 55k/EIP. High-throughput transfers (many parallel connections) hit this. Multiple NAT Gateways or multiple EIPs per NAT increase capacity."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company designs highly available database infrastructure across AZs. They implement read replicas in different AZs for failover. During AZ failure, RTO is 60 seconds due to failover detection + DNS update. What reduces RTO further?","options":["A. 60 seconds is optimal","B. Use Aurora multi-master with automatic failover (< 5s RTO) OR database connection pooling with health checks + application-side circuit breaker for faster recovery","C. RTO cannot improve","D. Requires manual failover"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aurora multi-master provides <5s failover without external tools. Connection pooling + application health checks reduce client reconnection time. Automatic failover faster than DNS-based."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements Network Firewall rule allowing traffic to HTTPS port 443 but blocks domain-based rules matching *.example.com. Legitimate traffic to *.example.com:443 is blocked. Why?","options":["A. Rules contradict each other","B. Firewall rule order matters. If block rule for *.example.com appears before allow port 443, block wins. Reorder rules: allow *.example.com first, then port-based rules","C. Cannot have both","D. Rules don't apply to HTTPS"],"answer":1,"explain":"Network Firewall rules evaluated in order. First match wins. Domain-based block before port-allow = block for all traffic to domain. Reorder: allow before block."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company monitoring Global Accelerator observes that one endpoint group has consistently high packet loss (5%) while others are <0.1%. This specific region endpoint has low latency though. What is the issue?","options":["A. Global Accelerator is misconfigured","B. Low latency + high loss suggests: congested region / degraded endpoint infrastructure / routing asymmetry to region. Check target health + capacity + BGP routing paths","C. Packet loss is acceptable","D. Change region"],"answer":1,"explain":"Latency doesn't correlate with reliability. Congested endpoints or degraded infrastructure cause loss despite good latency. Monitor targets + adjust traffic dials + investigate endpoint issues."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements AWS App Mesh for microservice networking to simplify service-to-service communication. They realize some microservices using legacy protocols (non-HTTP) cannot use App Mesh. What alternative provides similar benefits?","options":["A. Only HTTP services supported","B. VPC Lattice (layer 3/4 networking) provides service mesh without protocol restriction + service discovery + load balancing for any protocol","C. Cannot mesh non-HTTP","D. Use load balancers per service"],"answer":1,"explain":"App Mesh is application-layer (HTTP/gRPC). VPC Lattice operates at network layer supporting any protocol. Both provide service discovery + load balancing but VPC Lattice is protocol-agnostic."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures AWS Client VPN with mutual TLS authentication. Client can connect but DNS queries for AWS resources timeout. On-premises DNS works fine through VPN. Why?","options":["A. VPN blocks DNS","B. Client VPN tunnel is up but DNS endpoints must be explicitly configured. Clients use default DNS unless VPN pushes Route 53 Resolver IPs via DHCP options","C. Client VPN requires special DNS config","D. On-premises DNS is required"],"answer":1,"explain":"Client VPN provides layer 3 connectivity only. DNS resolution depends on client DNS configuration. VPN endpoint settings can push DNS servers to clients. Without push, clients use default DNS."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with geographically distributed data centers implementing AWS Outposts realizes that data residency requirements prevent data replication across regions. How can they achieve HA?","options":["A. HA requires replication","B. Within single Outpost: active-active across multiple AZs + cross-AZ redundancy for appliances + local backup storage + RTO/RPO acceptance within single location","C. Cannot have HA","D. Must use public AWS regions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Data residency + Outposts = local HA only. Cross-AZ redundancy within facility + multi-appliance design provides HA without region replication. RTO/RPO limited by single location."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements security group referencing where SG-A allows traffic from SG-B and vice versa (mutual allow). Applications using these SGs report connection failures randomly. What is the issue?","options":["A. Circular SG references work","B. Mutual SG references may create race conditions or incomplete propagation during rapid changes. Ensure: both directions configured + test connectivity + consider NACL baseline deny","C. Cannot use mutual references","D. Requires different approach"],"answer":1,"explain":"Circular SG references should work but rapid scaling or changes can cause propagation delays. Add explicit NACL allows + allow rules + test after config changes for propagation."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements NLB with TLS termination for HTTPS health checks to backend servers. Health checks pass but actual client connections timeout. What is missing?","options":["A. Health checks and client traffic are the same","B. NLB TLS termination must match client protocol. If health checks succeed (port open, TLS handshake) but client connections fail, likely: certificate mismatch / cipher suite incompatibility","C. Cannot mix TLS on health/client","D. Requires separate health checks"],"answer":1,"explain":"NLB TLS health check verifies port + TLS handshake. Client connection failure after passing health check indicates: certificate hostname mismatch / client cipher suite not supported / backend certificate issue."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing Route 53 multivalue answer routing expects load balancing across multiple IP addresses. They notice that some clients consistently receive only one address despite configuring multiple values. Why?","options":["A. Multivalue returns all addresses","B. Multivalue returns up to 8 healthy addresses + client-side caching + resolver behavior. Some resolvers/clients may cache single answer. Ensure: health checks functional + diverse IP set","C. Multivalue does not balance","D. Requires different routing policy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multivalue returns multiple addresses but client caching or resolver behavior may reuse single answer. Health check failures can reduce returned set. Monitor health + cache behavior."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements NLB behind AWS WAF with rules blocking known malicious IPs. Attack traffic from new IPs bypasses WAF (shows as ALLOWED in logs). What WAF strategy addresses zero-day IPs?","options":["A. WAF IP lists only","B. WAF IP reputation lists + rate-limiting rules + automated rule updates via AWS threat intelligence + assume breach (defense in depth with app-layer monitoring)","C. Cannot block unknown IPs","D. Disable WAF for research"],"answer":1,"explain":"Known IP blocking is reactive. Zero-day IPs bypass. Rate-limiting detects attack patterns (many requests from single IP). AWS Threat Intelligence feeds update rules. Assume some traffic escapes WAF."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company monitoring CloudFront distribution observes that cache hit ratio is 60% despite static content with long cache TTL. What causes low hit ratio?","options":["A. Cache hit ratio depends on content only","B. Low hit ratio: query string variations (param?v=1 vs param?v=2 = different cache keys) + custom headers + IP-based routing. Solution: normalize cache keys / disable query string variation","C. Cannot improve","D. Content is not cacheable"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront cache keys include query strings by default. Different query strings = different cache entries. Normalize query strings or disable query string forwarding to improve hit ratio."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company requiring sub-second latency between data centers and AWS implements multiple Direct Connect connections across different AWS DX locations. During one location's maintenance, failover introduces 500ms latency spike. What can reduce this?","options":["A. Direct Connect failover is optimal","B. Failover latency due to BGP convergence + routing updates. Reduce by: pre-configured backup paths + BGP fast convergence settings + pre-warmed connections on backup link","C. Cannot improve failover","D. Accept the spike"],"answer":1,"explain":"BGP convergence (30-45s) causes traffic loss. Pre-configured equal-cost backup paths + aggressive BGP timers reduce convergence. Some traffic shift during failover is unavoidable."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures bidirectional peering between two VPCs for resource sharing. They realize that one peering route is not appearing in the accepting VPC's route table. What did they forget?","options":["A. Peering automatically creates routes","B. Peering connection requires manual route table entries on both sides. Accepting VPC must add route pointing to peer CIDR via peering connection","C. Routes are automatic","D. Peering is one-directional"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC peering enables reachability but routes are not automatic. Both VPCs must add route table entries pointing to peer CIDR via peering connection. Manual or dynamic (via Transit Gateway) required."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements PrivateLink endpoint service for internal payment processing. External customers can create interface endpoints but some cannot authenticate to the service. What authorization layers exist?","options":["A. Producer service only","B. PrivateLink has multiple auth layers: producer service endpoint policy + producer application authentication + consumer IAM role + network connectivity. All must allow","C. Cannot require authentication","D. Only endpoint policy matters"],"answer":1,"explain":"PrivateLink provides network reachability but authorization happens at multiple layers. Producer endpoint policy controls which consumers can connect. Application-layer auth on producer validates consumer credentials."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with 10+ microservices implements service mesh via VPC Lattice for simplified networking. What monitoring must they implement since traditional VPC Flow Logs are less granular at application level?","options":["A. VPC Flow Logs are sufficient","B. Lattice provides service-level metrics but not application observability. Implement: Lattice access logs + X-Ray for tracing + CloudWatch Insights for service correlation","C. Cannot monitor Lattice","D. Disable monitoring for performance"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lattice abstracts network layer but introduces service layer. Lattice logs + X-Ray tracing needed for application observability. VPC Flow Logs insufficient for service-level correlation."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implementing AWS Client VPN with username/password authentication realizes that OpenVPN client on remote workers requires configuration management. What is the most scalable authentication approach?","options":["A. Username/password only","B. Federated authentication via AWS IAM / SAML / OAuth2 provides centralized management + single sign-on + reduced manual configuration","C. Only username/password","D. Manual configuration required"],"answer":1,"explain":"Client VPN supports SAML-based federation for SSO. Users authenticate via corporate identity provider. No manual certificate distribution. Centralized user management at scale."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements VPC endpoint service for third-party API platform. The platform provider makes updates and endpoint connectivity fails. Where should customers check first for issues?","options":["A. Customer side only","B. Troubleshoot both sides: customer interface endpoint configuration + customer route tables + producer service endpoint health + producer service availability. Health check failures indicate provider issues","C. Provider always responsible","D. Connection should never fail"],"answer":1,"explain":"Endpoint connectivity requires both sides. Customer issues: endpoint created, route table entry, SG allows. Provider issues: service endpoint health, service availability. Bidirectional troubleshooting required."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company analyzing VPC Flow Logs over 24 hours detects that a specific subnet pair has REJECTED 500k flows during night hours (2-4am) but ACCEPTED during day. This pattern repeats daily. What does this indicate?","options":["A. Misconfiguration","B. Regular pattern suggests scheduled process / backup / maintenance running at night that violates firewall rules. Correlate with: cron jobs / scheduled tasks / maintenance windows + update firewall rules","C. Random failures","D. Network issue"],"answer":1,"explain":"Predictable pattern indicates scheduled activity. Automated backups/sync jobs at night hitting firewall rules. Update rules or schedule to accommodate. VPC Flow Logs reveal operational patterns."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements Elastic Load Balancer with health checks on TCP:443 to HTTPS applications. Health checks pass but some requests from real clients receive connection reset. What is mismatch?","options":["A. Health checks are accurate","B. TCP health check only verifies port is open (TCP handshake succeeds). Real clients perform TLS handshake / send HTTP requests. Application errors not caught. Use HTTPS health checks","C. Cannot improve","D. Targets are broken"],"answer":1,"explain":"TCP health checks only verify TCP port open. HTTPS health check validates TLS + HTTP response codes. Mismatch between TCP passing + HTTPS failing indicates TLS/certificate issues on targets."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing VPC Lattice discovers that some services cannot communicate despite both being registered in the service network. What configuration is required for cross-service communication?","options":["A. Services auto-discover","B. Services must be in same service network + network policy must allow source to destination + authentication policies allow + security groups permit","C. Cannot limit communication","D. Requires separate network"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lattice service network enables discovery but policies control actual communication. Network ACLs, authentication policies, and security groups still apply. Configure all three."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements IPv6-only subnet in VPC for new workloads. EC2 instances launch successfully with IPv6 but cannot reach Systems Manager Session Manager for management. Why?","options":["A. IPv6 is fully supported","B. Session Manager requires VPC endpoint but default endpoints are IPv4-only. Must enable IPv6 on VPC endpoint (if supported) OR use NAT6 gateway as workaround","C. Cannot use Session Manager with IPv6","D. Requires public internet"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS services gradually add IPv6 support. Session Manager VPC endpoint may IPv6-only require workaround. Systems Manager endpoints need IPv6 addresses or dual-stack configuration."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements AWS Network Firewall between corporate network and internet. Some users report that video conferencing hangs intermittently. Firewall logs show no blocks. What is the issue?","options":["A. Firewall is working","B. Stateful firewall may drop bidirectional traffic if connection tracking timeouts during silence (video pause). UDP-based protocols need higher timeout settings + fragmentation handling","C. Cannot handle video","D. Firewall is broken"],"answer":1,"explain":"Video conferencing uses UDP with pauses. Firewall stateful tracking may timeout connection during silence, dropping subsequent packets. Increase UDP timeout (default 60s) for long-lived connections."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company deploying machine learning model training on EC2 GPU instances across multiple AZs realizes cross-AZ traffic costs exceed compute costs. What architecture minimizes inter-AZ transfers?","options":["A. Accept cross-AZ cost","B. Single-AZ deployment + HPC Cluster Placement Group for extreme throughput + EFA for low latency + managed storage (EBS) in same AZ + Data Cache for distributed caching","C. Cannot optimize","D. Move to on-premises"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cross-AZ HA incompatible with cost optimization for large data transfers. Choose: HA (pay inter-AZ) OR cost optimization (single AZ). Cluster Placement Group minimizes latency in single AZ."},{"cat":"network-management","q":"A company implementing Reachability Analyzer between sensitive instances shows 'reachable' but security audit claims network is properly isolated. Should they trust Reachability Analyzer result?","options":["A. Trust fully","B. Reachability Analyzer shows network-layer connectivity only. Security isolation requires multiple layers: network + IAM + resource policies + data encryption. Reachable ≠ secure","C. Should not use Analyzer","D. Only network isolation matters"],"answer":1,"explain":"Reachability Analyzer = network connectivity. Security isolation = network + application + encryption. Reachable ≠ insecure. Coordinate with security audit for all layers."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements Active/Passive failover with Route 53 health checks. Primary endpoint health check fails and failover completes in 60 seconds but business reports 120 seconds downtime. Why the discrepancy?","options":["A. Failover time matches DNS update","B. Failover (detection + Route 53 update ~30s) is fast but clients have DNS TTL (usually 300s). Clients continue using old cached IP for up to TTL before trying new IP. Cache + timeout = 120s","C. Route 53 is slow","D. Clients should retry faster"],"answer":1,"explain":"Health check detection (10-30s) + Route 53 update (fast) but client DNS TTL (300s by default) means old IP remains cached. Actual recovery = health detection + TTL wait. Lower TTL reduces real RTO."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing Global Accelerator for DDoS mitigation realizes that Global Accelerator provides layer 3/4 protection but application-layer DDoS (HTTP flooding, slowloris) still cause issues. What additional protection is needed?","options":["A. Global Accelerator covers all DDoS","B. Global Accelerator + Shield Advanced (L3/L4) + WAF (L7 application) required for comprehensive DDoS protection","C. Cannot protect application layer","D. Requires custom appliance"],"answer":1,"explain":"DDoS protection layered: L3/L4 (Global Accelerator + Shield) + L7 (WAF). Application-layer attacks (HTTP slow, cache bypass) bypass network protection. WAF essential for application DDoS."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company configures S3 bucket policies to restrict access via VPC endpoint. Some applications in VPC can still access S3 via internet despite endpoint policy. Why does endpoint policy not enforce access?","options":["A. Endpoint policy enforces all S3 access","B. Endpoint policy controls only traffic through endpoint. Applications using internet gateway bypass endpoint entirely. Enforce via: NAT removal + route table preventing internet egress to S3 IPs","C. Cannot restrict internet access","D. Bucket policy only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Endpoint policy works for traffic through endpoint. Applications reaching S3 via internet gateway bypass endpoint + policy. Remove internet route or use restrictive NACL to enforce endpoint use."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implements Network Firewall with rule allowing traffic to specific domain (*.example.com). However, domain is hosted on CDN with multiple IP addresses changing frequently. Rules don't catch all IPs. What is the solution?","options":["A. IP-based rules only","B. Network Firewall domain-based rules (SNI inspection) or use dynamic IP group rules that automatically track domain IPs via prefix lists / external intelligence feeds","C. Cannot track dynamic IPs","D. Requires manual updates"],"answer":1,"explain":"SNI inspection matches domain in TLS handshake, enabling domain-based rules regardless of IP. Prefix lists auto-update. Dynamic IP tracking via threat intelligence feeds."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company designs disaster recovery with simultaneous multi-region deployment. They implement Route 53 geoproximity routing assuming it provides automatic failover. During regional degradation, traffic still routes to degraded region. What is the issue?","options":["A. Geoproximity auto-failovers","B. Geoproximity routes by geography only. Failover requires health checks. Configure: geoproximity + health checks + failover policy combination for automatic failover on degradation","C. Cannot failover geoproximity","D. Manual intervention required"],"answer":1,"explain":"Geoproximity is purely geographic routing (no health awareness). Failover requires health checks. Combine policies: geoproximity for initial routing + health checks for failover logic."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements Site-to-Site VPN with automatic failover between primary and backup tunnels. During failover testing, both tunnels show 'up' status in console but traffic doesn't fail over. What is the issue?","options":["A. VPN failover is automatic","B. Both tunnels 'up' doesn't guarantee both carry traffic. BGP configuration determines traffic split. For true failover: primary tunnel must have higher priority (local preference) + traffic diverts to backup only on primary failure","C. Cannot failover tunnels","D. Requires manual selection"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPN dual tunnel redundancy requires BGP configuration for traffic steering. Default is equal-cost split. Configure: primary with higher local preference, backup as fallback only."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company with VPC in us-west-2 requires data residency in eu-west-1. They implement cross-region VPC peering for application connectivity. Does this violate data residency requirements?","options":["A. Peering is just connectivity","B. Peering provides only network path. Data residency depends on where data is stored. VPC peering alone doesn't move data. Applications using peering must not copy data between regions","C. Peering moves data","D. Violates residency automatically"],"answer":1,"explain":"Peering is network connectivity only. Data residency depends on storage location (RDS region, S3 bucket region). Cross-region peering allows apps to communicate but doesn't force data movement. Enforce at storage layer."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implementing NLB with target group pointing to IP addresses (not instances) realizes that some IPs show as unhealthy without reason. Health check configuration appears correct. What could be wrong?","options":["A. IPs are reachable","B. Health checks on non-instance IPs require network accessibility. Issue may be: traffic from NLB subnet not allowed in NACL/SG of target IP's network / target IP misconfigured / health check port closed","C. Cannot use IP targets","D. NLB is broken"],"answer":1,"explain":"IP-based targets require network connectivity from NLB to target. Check: NACLs on target network allow NLB health check traffic + target application responds to health check port + routing configured."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implements redundant NAT Instances across multiple subnets but realizes all instances route through single NAT (primary). When primary NAT Instance fails, all subnets lose connectivity. What is the architecture problem?","options":["A. Single NAT is correct","B. All subnets using same route table pointing to single NAT = SPOF. Separate route tables per AZ, each pointing to local NAT in that AZ + failover mechanism for individual NAT failure","C. Cannot have redundant NAT","D. Requires NAT Gateway"],"answer":1,"explain":"NAT Instance redundancy requires AZ-local design: route table per AZ → local NAT. Shared route table → SPOF. Multiple NAT Instances don't help unless routing isolates them."},{"cat":"network-security","q":"A company implementing security groups for containers in ECS realizes that updating SG rules to restrict a compromised container affects all containers using that SG. What is the trade-off between granularity and manageability?","options":["A. Use shared SGs for simplicity","B. Shared SGs efficient but affect all members. Task-level SGs (per container) provide isolation but increase complexity. Solutions: SG per environment/tier (not per container) + Network policies for fine-grained control","C. Cannot balance both","D. Individual SG per container"],"answer":1,"explain":"SG design trade-off: shared (simple, broad blast radius) vs. granular (complex, isolated). Recommendation: SG per application tier + Network policies (container-level) for fine-grained security."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implements Transit Gateway with attachment to 50 VPCs. One attachment fails to create route entries in its route table. Application traffic to other VPCs fails. What is required on the spoke VPC side?","options":["A. Attachment creation is sufficient","B. TGW attachment requires: route table entries in spoke pointing to TGW for destination networks + TGW route tables configured to accept/propagate spoke routes","C. Routes are automatic","D. TGW handles routing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transit Gateway enables attachment but routing is explicit. Spoke route tables must have entries pointing to TGW. TGW route tables must propagate or explicitly contain spoke CIDR blocks."},{"cat":"network-design","q":"A company implementing CloudFront with private S3 bucket origin enables OAI (Origin Access Identity). CloudFront can access S3 but some objects return 403 Forbidden to end users. What is the issue?","options":["A. OAI prevents access","B. OAI controls access to origin but S3 bucket versioning, ACLs, or object-level policies may restrict individual objects. S3 object policies must permit OAI + ensure objects are not private","C. Cannot restrict with OAI","D. Bucket policy alone"],"answer":1,"explain":"OAI allows CloudFront to access S3 but doesn't override object-level restrictions. S3 ACLs or per-object policies may block specific objects. Verify bucket policy + object ACLs."},{"cat":"network-implementation","q":"A company implementing CloudFront with failover between two origins notices that during primary origin failure, CloudFront still attempts requests to primary for 30+ seconds before failing over. How to detect primary failure faster?","options":["A. CloudFront auto-detects failures","B. CloudFront depends on HTTP status codes + TTL to detect failure. Configure: custom health checks returning failure codes quickly + lower error TTL (e.g., 10s for 5xx) + origin timeout settings","C. Cannot speed detection","D. Disable caching for detection"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudFront origin failover speed depends on detecting errors. Lower error response TTL + faster origin timeout reduce detection latency. Default 300s TTL for errors causes 30s+ delay before failover."}];